# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andreas-storm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andreas-storm/andreas-storm] After graduating from high school in 1983, Storm studied economics at the Johann Wolfgang Goethe University in Frankfurt am Main, graduating in 1988 with a degree in economics.
[src:andreas-storm/andreas-storm] He then worked as a research associate at the Institute for Development, Environment and Quantitative Economic Research.
[src:andreas-storm/andreas-storm] In 1990, he moved to the policy department of the Federal Ministry for Economic Affairs and Energy as a consultant.
[src:andreas-storm/andreas-storm] On July 1, 2016, he joined the board of DAK-Gesundheit and took over as chairman of the board on January 1, 2017.
[src:andreas-storm/andreas-storm] In December 2021, Storm was re-elected by the administrative board of DAK-Gesundheit for another six years.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt holds the official title "City of Science" (German: *Wissenschaftsstadt*) as it is a major centre of scientific institutions, universities, and high-technology companies.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The existence of several elements was also confirmed at the GSI Centre.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Facility for Antiproton and Ion Research (FAIR) is an international accelerator facility under construction.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt is also the seat of the world's oldest pharmaceutical company, Merck, which is the city's largest employer.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt was formerly the capital of a sovereign state, the Grand Duchy of Hesse and its successor, the People's State of Hesse, a federal state of Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] As the capital of an increasingly prosperous duchy, the city gained some international prominence and remains one of the wealthiest cities in Europe.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] In the 20th century, industry (especially chemicals), as well as large science and electronics (and later, information technology) sectors became increasingly important, and are still a major part of the city's economy.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It is also home to the football club SV Darmstadt 98.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Alexandra Feodorovna (Alix of Hesse), the wife of Nicholas II of Russia, as well as Maria Alexandrovna (Marie of Hesse), the wife of Alexander II of Russia, who were related, were born in this city.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The name Darmstadt first appears towards the end of the 11th century, then as *Darmundestat*.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt was chartered as a city by the Holy Roman Emperor Ludwig the Bavarian in 1330, at which time it belonged to the counts of Katzenelnbogen.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The city, then called *Darmstait*, became a secondary residence for the counts, with a small castle established at the site of the current, much larger edifice.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] When the house of Katzenelnbogen became extinct in 1479, the city was passed to the Landgraviate of Hesse, and was seat of the ruling landgraves (1567–1806) and thereafter (to 1918) of the grand dukes of Hesse.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The city's population grew during the 19th century, from a little over 10,000, to 72,000 inhabitants.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] A polytechnical school, which later became a Technical University now known as TU Darmstadt, was established in 1877.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] In the early 20th century, Darmstadt was an important centre for the art movement of Jugendstil, the German variant of Art Nouveau.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Also during this period, in 1912 the chemist Anton Kollisch, working for the pharmaceutical company Merck, first synthesised the chemical MDMA (ecstasy) in Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt's municipal area was extended in 1937 to include the neighbouring localities of Arheilgen and Eberstadt, and in 1938 the city was separated administratively from the surrounding district (*Kreis*).
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt was the first city in Germany to force Jewish shops to close in early 1933, shortly after the Nazis took power in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The shops were only closed for one day, for "endangering communal order and tranquility".
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] In 1942, over 3,000 Jews from Darmstadt were first forced into a collection camp located in the Liebigschule, and later deported to concentration camps where most eventually died.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] In 1944, the city was also the location of a subcamp of the Natzweiler-Struthof concentration camp.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Several prominent members of the German resistance movement against the Nazis were citizens of Darmstadt, including Wilhelm Leuschner and Theodor Haubach, both executed for their opposition to Hitler's regime.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt was first bombed on 30 July 1940, and 34 other air raids would follow before the war's end.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The old city centre was largely destroyed in a British bombing raid on 11/12 September 1944.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] This attack was an example of "area bombing" using high explosive and incendiary bombs, which combined in that attack to create a firestorm, a self-sustaining combustion process in which winds generated by the fire ensure it continues to burn until everything possible has been consumed.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] During this attack, an estimated 11,000 to 12,500 of the inhabitants were killed, and 66,000 to 70,000 were left homeless.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Over three-quarters of Darmstadt's inner city was destroyed.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Post-war rebuilding was done in a relatively plain architectural style, although a number of the historic buildings were rebuilt to their original appearance following the city's capture on 25 March 1945 by the American 4th Armored Division.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Today around 30% of Darmstadt consists of buildings from before World War II.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, Darmstadt became home to many technology companies and research institutes, and has been promoting itself as a "city of science" since 1997.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] In 2000, its region also scored Rank 3 amongst 97 German regions in the *WirtschaftsWoche* test ranking Germany's high-tech regions.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The TU Darmstadt is one of the important technical institutes in Germany and is well known for its research and teaching in the Electrical, Mechanical, Material and Civil Engineering disciplines.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Together with other tertiary institutions, the TU is responsible for the large student population of the city, which stood at 33,547 in 2004.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt has nine official 'Stadtteile' (boroughs).
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The current mayor of Darmstadt is Hanno Benz of SPD, who was elected in 2023.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Darmstadt city council (*Stadtverordnetenversammlung*) governs the city alongside the Mayor.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt is connected to a number of major roads, including two Autobahnen (Bundesautobahn 5 and Bundesautobahn 67).
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The main road passing west–east is the Bundesstraße 26, the Bundesstraße 3 runs north–south.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The rural areas east of the city in the Odenwald are accessed by several secondary roads.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt is connected to the rest of Germany and Europe through its main railway station, Darmstadt Hauptbahnhof, which is located in the western part of the city centre.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The station is part of the Intercity-Express network and also served by other long-distance trains.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It is a busy station with 12 platforms and serves as a transportation hub for the southern Hesse/Odenwald region.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt Hauptbahnhof is the terminus of on the Rhine-Main S-Bahn, which connects the city to Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Within Darmstadt the S6 also stops at stations in Darmstadt-Arheilgen and Darmstadt-Wixhausen.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Regional trains also connect six secondary railway stations within Darmstadt, and stations in the surrounding region, with Darmstadt Hauptbahnhof.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The extensive public transport system of Darmstadt is integrated in the RMV (the transportation authority of the Rhein-Main Metropolitan Area).
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The backbone of public transport in Darmstadt is the tram system with 10 lines.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Local bus lines also serve all parts of the city and the city is served by regional bus lines.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The historically important local airfield August Euler Airfield is closed to aviation at large, being reserved for the use of the Technische Universität Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt can be easily accessed from around the world via Frankfurt Airport (*Flughafen Frankfurt am Main*) which is located 20 km (12 mi) north of central Darmstadt and connected to it via Autobahn 5, S-Bahn, several bus lines and a direct express bus-link ("*Airliner*").
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The airport ranks among the world's busiest airports by passenger traffic and is the second-busiest airport by cargo traffic in Europe.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The airport also serves as the main hub for German flag carrier Lufthansa.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Frankfurt Egelsbach Airport (*Flugplatz Frankfurt-Egelsbach*) is a busy general aviation airport located 5 km north of Darmstadt, near the town of Egelsbach.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Despite the name, Frankfurt Hahn Airport (*Flughafen Frankfurt-Hahn*) is located far outside the Frankfurt Metro Area, approximately 120 km (75 mi) to the west in Lautzenhausen (Rhineland-Palatinate).
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Hahn Airport is a major base for low-cost carrier Ryanair.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] This airport can only be reached by car or bus.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt is served by several national and European bus links which connect Darmstadt with other German and European cities.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt was the capital of an independent country (the Grand Duchy of Hesse) until 1871 and the capital of the German state of Hesse until 1945.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It is due to its past as a capital city that it has many architectural testimonies of this period.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Many of its major architectural landmarks were created by Georg Moller who was appointed the court master builder of the Grand Duchy of Hesse.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Residential Palace Darmstadt (*Stadtschloss*) is located in the city centre.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It was the residence of the counts of Hesse-Darmstadt, later as Grand Dukes of Hesse by the grace of Napoleon.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The rulers of Hesse also owned Jagdschloss Kranichstein, a hunting lodge in Kranichstein which is a nowadays used as a five star hotel.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The most famous castle in the Darmstadt region is Frankenstein Castle due to claims that the real castle may have had an influence on Mary Shelley's decision to choose the name Frankenstein for her monster-creating scientist.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] This castle dates back to the 13th century, but it was acquired by the counts of Hesse-Darmstadt in 1662.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The last ruling Grand Duke of Hesse, Ernst Ludwig was a grandson of Queen Victoria and brother to Empress Alexandra of Russia.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The architecture of Darmstadt has been influenced by British and Russian imperial architecture with many examples still existing, such as the Luisenplatz with its grand-ducal column, the old Hessian State Theatre and the Russian Chapel in Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Russian Chapel is a Russian orthodox church which is still in use.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It was built and used as a private chapel by the last Tsar of Russia, Nicholas II, whose wife Alexandra was born in Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Although Russian orthodox churches also exist in other cities outside Russia, the Russian Chapel in Darmstadt was the only official Russian church used by the Tsar outside the Russian Empire.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It is said that the chapel was built on Russian soil that was brought to Darmstadt exclusively for the purpose of building the Tsar's private chapel on it. by Leon Benois.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Mary Magdalene Chapel, is named in honor of the patron saint of Tsar Nicholas' mother and was built of Russian stone on Russian soil brought to Darmstadt by train.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It was used by the Russian imperial family and court during regular visits to the Tsarina's brother and family in Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt has a rich tradition in modern architecture.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] After 1945 several *"Meisterbauten"* (*Masterful Architectonic Creations*) were built that set standards for modern architecture.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] These buildings still exist and are used for various public and private purposes.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] In the late 1990s the Waldspirale ('Forest Spiral') was built, a residential complex by Austrian Friedensreich Hundertwasser.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] As an almost surreal building, it is internationally famous for its almost absolute rejection of rectangular forms, down to every window having a different shape, the style being a trademark of Hundertwasser's work.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Hundertwasser died before the Waldspirale was finished.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt was a centre of the Art Nouveau movement.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] German Art Nouveau is commonly known by its German name, Jugendstil.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The name is taken from the artistic journal, Die Jugend, which was published in Munich and which espoused the new artistic movement.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It was founded in 1896 by Georg Hirth (Hirth remained editor until his death in 1916, and the magazine continued to be published until 1940).
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The magazine was instrumental in promoting the style in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] As a result, its name was adopted as the most common German-language term for the style: Jugendstil ("young style").
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The two main centres for Jugendstil art in Germany were Munich and Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The *Luisenplatz*, the central square of the city, forms the centre of the city and is the main public transport hub.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] In 1844 the *Ludwigsäule* (called *Langer Lui*, meaning *Long Ludwig*), a 33-metre (108 ft) column commemorating Ludwig I, first Grand Duke of Hesse, was placed in the middle of the square.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] While the column still stands, the square is today surrounded by mostly modern buildings.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Other important squares are the *Marktplatz* (see image) near the old city hall and the *Sabaisplatz* at the *Mathildenhöhe*.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Among the most important parks are the English style *Herrngarten* in central Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] In former times it was part of the Royal Gardens used exclusively by the dukes of Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Today it is a public park, heavily used in every season of the year.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The *Botanischer Garten* in eastern Darmstadt is a botanical garden maintained by the Technische Universität Darmstadt with a fine collection of rare plants and trees.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Protestant Stadtkirche Darmstadt built in 1369, is in the pedestrian zone of the downtown city center, next to the historic Hotel Bockshaut.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The church has gothic elements along with renaissance and baroque, it houses the royal crypt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Hotel Bockshaut was built in 1580 for a church presbytery.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The most important Catholic Church is *St.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Every year on the first weekend of July the Heinerfest festival is held in the streets surrounding the old ducal palace.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It is a traditional German festival with music acts, beer halls, amusement rides and booths selling trinkets and food.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Schlossgrabenfest, better known as the Stage Groove Festival, is live music-oriented and is held every year in May.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] These two festivals attract 700,000 and 400,000 visitors respectively.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Staatstheater Darmstadt dates back to the year 1711.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The present building has been in use since 1972 and has three halls which can be used independently.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The "Grand Hall" (Großes Haus) provides seats for 956 people and serves as Darmstadt's opera house.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The "Small Hall" (Kleines Haus) is mostly used for plays and dance and has 482 seats.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] A separate small hall (Kammerspiele), with 120 seats, is used for chamber plays.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Darmstadt Palace Museum collection showcases regional and royal history from the 16th until the early 20th Century.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Palace Museum consists of 16 showrooms.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Jazz-Institut Darmstadt is Germany's largest publicly accessible jazz archive.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Internationales Musikinstitut Darmstadt, harboring one of the world's largest collections of post-war sheet music, also hosts the biennial Internationale Ferienkurse für Neue Musik, a summer school in contemporary classical music founded by Wolfgang Steinecke.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] A large number of avant-garde composers have attended and given lectures there, including Olivier Messiaen, Luciano Berio, Milton Babbitt, Pierre Boulez, Luigi Nono, John Cage, György Ligeti, Iannis Xenakis, Karlheinz Stockhausen, Mauricio Kagel, and Helmut Lachenmann.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Deutsche Akademie für Sprache und Dichtung provides writers and scholars with a place to research the German language.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The academy's annual Georg Büchner Prize, named in memory of Georg Büchner, is considered the most prestigious literary award for writers of German language.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt is located in the Upper Rhine Plain (German: Oberrheinische Tiefebene), a major rift, about 350 km (217 mi) long and on average 50 km (31 mi) wide, between the cities of Frankfurt in the north and Mannheim in the south.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt's southeastern boroughs are located in the spurs of the Odenwald, a low mountain range in Southern Hesse between the Main and Neckar rivers.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Southern Hesse is well known for its mild climate which allows winegrowing on a large scale in the region south of Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The weather is often volatile with the summers being warm and humid with frequent thunderstorms, the winters mostly relatively mild with frequent periods of high fog.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Snowfall is most likely in January and February, but mild winters without considerable snowfall can occur.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The City of Darmstadt offers students a broad variety of public primary, secondary and tertiary schools.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Besides them private schools exist, e.g. the catholic secondary school *Edith-Stein-Schule*, the Adventists' *Schulzentrum Marienhöhe*, an anthroposophic *Waldorf School*, a *Comenius* *School* and other faith based private schools.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Technical University of Darmstadt (German: *Technische Universität Darmstadt*), commonly referred to as TU Darmstadt, is a prestigious research university in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It was founded in 1877 and received the right to award doctorates in 1899.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] In 1882 it was the first university in the world to set up a chair in electrical engineering, in 1883 the first faculty for electrical engineering was founded there.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The university is organized in 13 departments and 5 fields of study, which all together offer about 100 courses of studies.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The fields of study offer interdisciplinary degree courses in which students take lectures in multiple departments.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The university, as its title suggests, offers degree courses in the fields of electrical, mechanical and civil engineering, architecture, computer science, mathematics and the natural sciences.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It also offers courses in economics, law, history, politics, sociology, psychology, sport science and linguistics.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It also offers degree courses for teaching positions at German vocational schools and Gymnasiums.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Darmstadt University of Applied Sciences (German: *Hochschule Darmstadt*) has the highest number of industrial linkage programs, compared to the rest of the universities of applied sciences.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The roots of University of Applied Sciences Darmstadt dates back to 1876.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] However, it has not emerged as a separate institution before 1971.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] As of 2017 it was the largest University of Applied Sciences in the State of Hesse, with about 16,000 students.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Protestant University of Applied Sciences Darmstadt (EHD) is an officially recognised and Church-sponsored University.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The sponsors are the Protestant Church in Hesse and Nassau, the Protestant Church of Kurhesse-Waldeck and the social welfare organisation of both Hessian Protestant Churches, the Diakonie Hesse.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The EHD has approximately 1,700 students, 40 professors and 10 scientific employees and about 100 visiting lecturers every semester.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The city's main professional club is the football club SV Darmstadt 98, who play at the Merck-Stadion am Böllenfalltor.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Darmstadt Dukes (Eissportclub Darmstadt Dukes) is an ice hockey club.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Their mens`s team is playing in the Hessenliga.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The city is home to the Darmstadt Diamonds an american football team.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt is home to many research institutions such as the Fraunhofer Society (Fraunhofer IGD, Fraunhofer LBF, Fraunhofer SIT) and the Gesellschaft für Schwerionenforschung (GSI, "Society for heavy ion Research"), which operates a particle accelerator in northern Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The GSI, amongst other elements, discovered the chemical element darmstadtium (atomic number: 110), named after the city in 2003.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] This makes Darmstadt one of several cities with elements named after them.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Various other elements, including meitnerium (atomic number: 109) (1982), hassium (atomic number: 108) (1984), roentgenium (atomic number: 111) (1994) and copernicium (atomic number: 112) (1996) were also synthesized in the Darmstadt facility.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The European Space Operations Centre (ESOC) of the European Space Agency is located in Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] From here, various deep-space exploration spacecraft and Earth-orbiting satellites are operated for the purposes of scientific research, and technology development and demonstration.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] EUMETSAT, the European Organisation for the Exploitation of Meteorological Satellites, operates the principal European meteorological satellites from its headquarters, including the first and second generations of Meteosat geostationary satellites, and the polar-orbiting Metop series.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt is a centre for the pharmaceutical and chemical industry, with Merck, Röhm and Schenck RoTec (part of The Dürr Group) having their main plants and centres here.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Darmstadt is also a centre for the IT and telecommunications industry, with companies like Software AG, T-Systems (laboratories in Darmstadt) and Deutsche Telekom (laboratories in Darmstadt).
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] ATHENE, formerly Center for Research in Security and Privacy (CRISP), is the national research center for IT security and privacy in Germany and the largest research center for IT security in Europe.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The research center is located in Darmstadt and deals with key issues of IT security in the digitization of government, business and society.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The German Research Center for Artificial Intelligence has a laboratory in Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The Hessian Center for Artificial Intelligence (hessian.AI) has its headquarters in Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] U.S. forces entered the city of Darmstadt on 25 March 1945.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] At the end of World War II, Darmstadt was among the 112 communities where U.S. forces were stationed.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Early units stationed here included elements of the U.S.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Constabulary, Air Force units and a Quartermaster School.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Over the years, the U.S. military community Darmstadt – under a variety of designations such as the 440th Signal Battalion, served as home for thousands of American soldiers and their families.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It included six principal installations in Darmstadt and nearby Babenhausen, Griesheim and Münster, plus several housing areas, an airfield and a large number of smaller facilities as far away as Bensheim and Aschaffenburg.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] The military newspaper European *Stars and Stripes* also had its headquarters there.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] As of 1993, the Darmstadt military community also assumed responsibility for the remaining U.S.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Army's ongoing transformation in Germany, the Darmstadt military community, by then designated U.S.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Army Garrison Darmstadt, inactivated on 30 September 2008.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Even after the garrison inactivation, however, there is still one unit active in Darmstadt: The 66th Military Intelligence Group at the Dagger Complex on Eberstädter Weg.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] It draws its support from the nearby U.S.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] Army Garrison Wiesbaden's website mentions the unit still being active in Darmstadt, and a Marine Corps company being stationed there as well.
[src:andreas-storm/darmstadt] With the exception of Dagger Complex, all remaining US installations are now empty and closed to the public, pending property disposal by the German authorities.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] The **Federal Ministry for Economic Affairs and Energy** (German: *Bundesministerium für Wirtschaft und Energie*, [ˈbʊndəsminɪsˌteːʁiʊm fyːɐ̯ ˈvɪʁt.ʃaft ʔʊnt eneʁˈɡiː]; abbreviated **BMWE**, formerly BMWK and BMWi) is a cabinet-level ministry of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] It was previously known as the "Ministry of Economy".
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] It was recreated in 2005 as "Ministry of Economics and Technology" after it had previously been merged with other ministries to form the Federal Ministry for Economics and Labour between 2002 and 2005.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] The ministry is advised by the Council of Advisors on Digital Economy.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] The historical predecessor of the current Federal Ministry for Economic Affairs and Climate Action was the *Reichswirtschaftsamt* (Reich Economic Office), founded in 1917.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] In 1919, this became the *Reichswirtschaftsministerium* (Reich Ministry of Economy), which existed until 1945.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] In postwar occupied Germany, its functions were exercised by the Administrative Office of Economy (German: *Verwaltungsamt für Wirtschaft*) between 1946 and 1949.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] After the founding of the Federal Republic of Germany, the Federal Ministry of Economics (German: *Bundesministerium für Wirtschaft*) existed from 1949 to 1998.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] From May 1971 to December 1972, it was temporarily merged with the Federal Ministry of Finance, in the Federal Ministry of Economics and Finance.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] In 1998 the technology section of the Ministry of Research was added, making it the Federal Ministry of Economics and Technology.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] Between 2002 and 2005, it was merged with the Federal Ministry of Economics and Technology and one part of the Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs - the other part being merged with the old Federal Ministry for Health, then the Ministry of Health and Social Security.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] This transformations aimed to consolidate the policy-fields of economics and labour market, on which the second term of chancellor Gerhard Schröder wanted to focus, into one hand.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] Because the new Ministry was very large and important, it was often referred to as a super-ministry (*Superministerium*) and its minister as a super-minister (*Superminister*).
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] The creation of the new Ministry was widely seen as failed, basically because of the poor performance of the only office-holder Wolfgang Clement.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] Under the following grand coalition headed by Angela Merkel, the portfolio reshuffle was reversed, and the old Federal Ministries of Economics and Technology, of Labour and Social Affairs and of Health were created once again as Federal Ministry of Economics and Technology.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] It was renamed to Federal Ministry for Economic Affairs and Energy in 2013.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] The Ministry is organised into 10 departments and one central department.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-for-economic-affairs-and-climate-action] The ministry is headquartered in Berlin.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] Its first location is on Wilhelmstrasse in Berlin, the second in Bonn.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] The Reich Ministry of Labour of the Weimar Republic was established on 13 February 1919 as the successor of the Labour Office (*Reichsarbeitsamt*) of the German Empire.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] The Social Democratic politician Gustav Bauer became the first Minister for Labour under Chancellor Philipp Scheidemann, whom he succeeded on 21 June that year.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] The West German Ministry for Labour was re-established in Bonn on 20 September 1949 with the Cabinet Adenauer I.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] According to the 1991 Berlin/Bonn Act it moved to its present seat in Berlin-Mitte in 2000, on premises formerly used by Goebbels' Propaganda Ministry and the East German National Front organisation.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] During the Cabinet Schröder II from 2002 to 2005, the ministry had been dissolved and its responsibilities allocated to the Federal Ministry for Economics and Labour and the Federal Ministry of Health and Social Security.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] Responsibilities were re-allocated once again when a new government was formed under Chancellor Angela Merkel following the Bundestag elections of 2005.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] The German name was changed from *Bundesministerium für Arbeit und Sozialordnung* to *Bundesministerium für Arbeit und Soziales*.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] As of May 2025, The Secretaries of State are Leonie Gebers, Lilian Tschan and Michael Schäfer.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] The ministry is located within the former Reich Ministry of Public Enlightenment and Propaganda.
[src:andreas-storm/federal-ministry-of-labour-and-social-affairs] For the building's interior courtyard, artist Daniel Buren was commissioned with his large-scale installation *La Grande Fenêtre* (2001).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt was first mentioned in a document in 794 and has been an imperial city since 1372.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] It has been part of the state of Hesse since 1945.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is culturally, ethnically and religiously diverse, with half of its population, and a majority of its young people, having a migrant background.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] A quarter of the population consists of foreign nationals, including many expatriates.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 2015, Frankfurt was home to 1,909 ultra high-net-worth individuals, the sixth-highest number of any city.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is a global hub for commerce, culture, education, tourism and transportation, and is the site of many global and European corporate headquarters.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Due to its central location in former West Germany, Frankfurt Airport became the busiest in Germany, one of the busiest in the world, the airport with the most direct routes in the world, and the primary hub for Lufthansa, the national airline of Germany and Europe's largest airline.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt Central Station is Germany's second-busiest railway station after Hamburg Hbf, operated by Deutsche Bahn, the world's largest railway company, whose Frankfurter division DB InfraGO manages the largest railway network in Europe.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurter Kreuz is the most-heavily used interchange in the EU.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is one of the major financial and business centers of Europe, with the headquarters of the European Central Bank, Deutsche Bundesbank, Frankfurt Stock Exchange, Deutsche Bank, DZ Bank, KfW, Commerzbank, DekaBank, Helaba, several cloud and fintech startups, and other institutes.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Automotive, technology and research, services, consulting, media and creative industries complement the economic base.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt's DE-CIX is the world's largest internet exchange point.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Messe Frankfurt is one of the world's largest trade fairs.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Other major fairs include the Music Fair and the Frankfurt Book Fair, the world's largest book fair.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The city also has 93 consulates, among which the largest is the US Consulate General.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is home to influential educational institutions, including the Goethe University with the Universitätsklinikum Frankfurt (Hesse's largest hospital), the FUAS, the FUMPA, and graduate schools like the FSFM.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The city is one of two seats of the German National Library (alongside Leipzig), the largest library in the German-speaking countries and one of the largest in the world.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Its renowned cultural venues include the concert hall Alte Oper, continental Europe's largest English theater and many museums, including the Städel, Liebieghaus, German Film Museum, Senckenberg Natural Museum, Goethe House and Schirn art venue.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt's skyline is shaped by some of Europe's tallest skyscrapers, which has led to the term *Mainhattan*.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The city has many parks and major botanical gardens.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Roughly 52 percent of the city area is green.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is a founding member of the Climate Alliance of European Cities and has pledged to work towards a 50 percent reduction of carbon emissions by 2030.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is the seat of the German Football Association, is home to the first division association football club Eintracht Frankfurt, the Löwen Frankfurt ice hockey team, and the basketball club Frankfurt Skyliners, and is the venue of the Frankfurt Marathon and the Ironman Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is the largest financial hub in continental Europe.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] It is home to the European Central Bank, Deutsche Bundesbank, Frankfurt Stock Exchange and several large commercial banks.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt has many high-rise buildings that form its renowned Frankfurt skyline.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In fact, it is one of the few cities in the European Union (EU) to have such a skyline.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Frankfurt Stock Exchange is one of the world's largest stock exchanges by market capitalization and accounts for more than 90 percent of the turnover in the German market.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 2010, 63 national and 152 international banks had their registered offices in Frankfurt, including Germany's major banks, notably Deutsche Bank, DZ Bank, KfW, Deka Bank and Commerzbank, as well as 41 representative offices of international banks.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt has been nicknamed Mainhattan and Bankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The city is also noted for its unique timber-framed old town.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Römer area has been most recently in the Dom-Römer Project and hosts the Frankfurt Christmas Market.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Saalgasse complements the timbered romanticism with postmodern houses by 12 different architectural firms.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is considered a global city as listed by the GaWC group's 2012 inventory.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Among global cities it was ranked tenth by the Global Power City Index 2011 and 11th by the Global City Competitiveness Index 2012.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Among financial hubs, the city was ranked eighth by the International Financial Centers Development Index 2013 and ninth in the 2013 Global Financial Centres Index.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Its central location in Germany and Europe makes Frankfurt a major air, rail, and road transport hub.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt Airport is one of the world's busiest international airports by passenger traffic and the main hub for Germany's flag carrier Lufthansa.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt Central Station is one of the largest rail stations in Europe and the busiest junction operated by Deutsche Bahn, the German national railway company, with 342 trains a day to domestic and European destinations.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurter Kreuz, also known as the Autobahn interchange and located close to the airport, is the most-heavily used interchange in the EU, used by 320,000 cars daily.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 2011, human-resource-consulting firm Mercer ranked Frankfurt as seventh in its annual "Quality of Living" survey of cities around the world.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] According to *The Economist* magazine's cost-of-living survey, Frankfurt is Germany's most expensive city and the world's 10th most expensive.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Thietmar of Merseburg in the 11th century reported a founding legend in which Charlemagne and his army of Franks discovered the ford at Frankfurt when a doe crossed over it, showing them the way; in honor of this, the city was named "ford of the Franks".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] By the 19th century, the name *Frankfurt* had been established as the official spelling.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The older English spelling of *Frankfort* is now rarely seen in reference to Frankfurt am Main, although more than a dozen other towns and cities, mainly in the United States, use this spelling, including Frankfort, Kentucky, Frankfort, New York, and Frankfort, Illinois.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] *The New York Times* first used the Frankfurt spelling for Frankfurt am Main on 24 October 1953 and last used the Frankfort spelling on 10 June 1954.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The suffix *am Main* has been used regularly since the 14th century.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In English, the city's full name of *Frankfurt am Main* means "Frankfurt on the Main" (pronounced like English *mine* or German *mein*).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is located on an ancient ford (German: **Furt**) on the river Main.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] As a part of early Franconia, the inhabitants were the early Franks, thus the city's name reveals its legacy as "the ford of the Franks on the Main".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Among English speakers, the city is commonly known simply as Frankfurt, but Germans occasionally call it by its full name to distinguish it from the other (significantly smaller) German city of Frankfurt an der Oder in the *Land* of Brandenburg on the Polish border.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The common abbreviations for the city, primarily used in railway services and on road signs, are *Frankfurt (Main)*, *Frankfurt (M)*, *Frankfurt a.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The common abbreviation for the name of the city is "FFM".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Also in use is "FRA", the IATA code for Frankfurt Airport.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] At the western borders of Frankfurt lies the Kapellenberg as part of the Taunus with one of the first Stone Age cities in Europe.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Celts had different settlements in the Taunus mountains north of Frankfurt, the biggest one the Heidetrank Oppidum.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The first traces of Roman settlements established in the area of the river Nidda date to the reign of Emperor Vespasian in the years 69 to 79 AD.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Nida (modern Heddernheim, Praunheim) was a Roman civitas capital (*Civitas Taunensium*).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Alemanni and Franks lived there, and by 794, Charlemagne presided over an imperial assembly and church synod, at which *Franconofurd* (alternative spellings end with -furt and -vurd) was first mentioned.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] It was one of the two capitals of Charlemagne's grandson Louis the German, together with Regensburg.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Louis founded the collegiate church, rededicated in 1239 to Bartholomew the Apostle and now Frankfurt Cathedral.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt was one of the most important cities in the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] From 855, the German kings were elected and crowned in Aachen.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 1372, Frankfurt became a *Reichsstadt* (Imperial Free City) and was as such directly subordinate to the Holy Roman Emperor rather than a regional ruler or a local nobleman.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] From 1562 onward the kings and emperors were crowned and elected in Frankfurt, starting with Maximilian II.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] This tradition ended in 1792, when Francis II was elected.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] His coronation was deliberately held on 14 July Bastille Day, the anniversary of the storming of the Bastille.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The elections and coronations took place in St.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Bartholomäus Cathedral, known as the *Kaiserdom* (Imperial Cathedral), or the four other structures known to have existed at this location.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The cathedral spire was constructed according to plans by Madern Gerthener in 1415 and is 95 meters tall.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Messe Frankfurt ('Frankfurt Trade Fair') was first mentioned in 1150.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 1240, Emperor Frederick II granted an imperial privilege to its visitors, meaning they would be protected by the empire.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The fair became particularly important when similar fairs in French Beaucaire lost attraction around 1380.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 1585, Frankfurt traders established a system of exchange rates for the various currencies that were circulating to prevent cheating and extortion.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Therein lay the early roots for the Frankfurt Stock Exchange.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt managed to remain neutral during the Thirty Years' War, but suffered from the bubonic plague that refugees brought to the city.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] After the war, Frankfurt regained its wealth.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In the late 1770s the theater principal Abel Seyler was based in Frankfurt, and established the city's theatrical life.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Following the French Revolution, Frankfurt was occupied or bombarded several times by French troops.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] It remained a Free city until the collapse of the Holy Roman Empire in 1805/6.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 1806, it became part of the principality of Aschaffenburg under the *Fürstprimas* (Prince-Primate), Karl Theodor Anton Maria von Dalberg.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] This meant that Frankfurt was incorporated into the Confederation of the Rhine.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 1810, Dalberg adopted the title of a Grand Duke of Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Napoleon intended to make his adopted son Eugène de Beauharnais, already *Prince de Venise* ("prince of Venice", a newly established primogeniture in Italy), Grand Duke of Frankfurt after Dalberg's death (since the latter as a Catholic bishop had no legitimate heirs).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Grand Duchy remained a short episode lasting from 1810 to 1813 when the military tide turned in favor of the Anglo-Prussian-led allies that overturned the Napoleonic order.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Dalberg abdicated in favor of Eugène de Beauharnais, which of course was only a symbolic action, as the latter effectively never ruled after the ruin of the French armies and Frankfurt's takeover by the allies.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] After Napoleon's final defeat and abdication, the Congress of Vienna (1814–1815) dissolved the grand-duchy and Frankfurt became a fully sovereign city-state with a republican form of government.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt entered the newly founded German Confederation (till 1866) as a free city, becoming the seat of its *Bundestag*, the confederal parliament where the nominally presiding Habsburg Emperor of Austria was represented by an Austrian "presidential envoy".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] After the ill-fated revolution of 1848, Frankfurt was the seat of the first democratically elected German parliament, the Frankfurt Parliament, which met in the *Frankfurter Paulskirche* (St.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Paul's Church) and was opened on 18 May 1848.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In the year of its existence, the assembly developed a common constitution for a unified Germany, with the Prussian king as its monarch.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The institution failed in 1849 when the Prussian king, Frederick William IV, declared that he would not accept "a crown from the gutter".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt lost its independence following the Austro-Prussian War of 1866, when Prussia annexed several smaller states, including the Free City of Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The city was subsequently incorporated into the Prussian province of Hesse-Nassau.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The occupation and annexation were widely regarded in Frankfurt as a grave injustice, yet the city retained its distinctly Western European, urban, and cosmopolitan character.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The formerly independent towns of Bornheim and Bockenheim were incorporated in 1890.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 1914, the citizens founded the University of Frankfurt, later named Goethe University Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] This marked the only civic foundation of a university in Germany; today it is one of Germany's largest.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] From 6 April to 17 May 1920, following military intervention to put down the Ruhr uprising, Frankfurt was occupied by French troops.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The French claimed that Articles 42 to 44 of the peace treaty of Versailles concerning the demilitarization of the Rhineland had been broken.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 1924, Ludwig Landmann became the first Jewish mayor of the city, and led a significant expansion during the following years.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] During the Nazi era, the synagogues of the city were destroyed and the vast majority of the Jewish population fled or was killed.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt was severely bombed in World War II (1939–1945).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] About 5,500 residents were killed during the raids, and the once-famous medieval city center, by that time one of the largest in Germany, was almost completely destroyed.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] It became a ground battlefield on 26 March 1945, when the Allied advance into Germany was forced to take the city in contested urban combat that included a river assault.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The 5th Infantry Division and the 6th Armored Division of the United States Army captured Frankfurt after several days of intense fighting, and it was declared largely secure on 29 March 1945.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In spite of the wartime destruction, more than 40% of Frankfurt's buildings still date from before the Second World War.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] After the end of the war, Frankfurt became a part of the newly founded state of Hesse, consisting of the old Hesse-(Darmstadt) and the Prussian Hesse provinces.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The city was part of the American Zone of Occupation of Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Military Governor for the United States Zone (1945–1949) and the United States High Commissioner for Germany (HICOG) (1949–1952) had their headquarters in the IG Farben Building, intentionally left undamaged by the Allies' wartime bombardment.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt was the original choice for the provisional capital city of the newly founded state of West Germany in 1949.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The city constructed a parliament building that was never used for its intended purpose (it housed the radio studios of Hessischer Rundfunk).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Postwar reconstruction took place in a sometimes simple modern style, thus changing Frankfurt's architectural face.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] A few landmark buildings were reconstructed historically, albeit in a simplified manner (e.g., Römer, St.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The collection of historically significant Cairo Genizah documents of the Municipal Library was destroyed by the bombing.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] According to Arabist and Genizah scholar S.D.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The end of the war marked Frankfurt's comeback as Germany's leading financial hub.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 1948, the Allies founded the Bank deutscher Länder, the forerunner of the Deutsche Bundesbank.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Following this decision, more financial institutions were re-established, such as Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In the 1950s, Frankfurt Stock Exchange regained its position as the country's leading stock exchange.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 1998, the European Central Bank was founded in Frankfurt, followed by the European Insurance and Occupational Pensions Authority in 2011, and the Anti-Money Laundering Authority in 2024.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt also reemerged as Germany's transportation hub and Frankfurt Airport became Europe's second-busiest airport behind London Heathrow Airport in 1961.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] During the 1970s, the city created one of Europe's most efficient underground transportation systems.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] That system includes a suburban rail system (S-Bahn) linking outlying communities with the city center, and a deep underground light rail system with smaller coaches (U-Bahn) also capable of travelling above ground on rails.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is the largest city in the state of Hesse in the western part of Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is located on both sides of the river Main, south-east of the Taunus mountain range.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The southern part of the city contains the Frankfurt City Forest, Germany's largest city forest.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Its downtown is north of the river Main in Altstadt district (the historical center) and the surrounding Innenstadt district.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The geographical center is in Bockenheim district near Frankfurt West station.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt at the heart of the densely populated Frankfurt Rhine-Main Metropolitan Region with a population of 5.5 million.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Other important cities in the region are Wiesbaden (capital of Hesse), Mainz (capital of Rhineland-Palatinate), Darmstadt, Offenbach am Main, Hanau, Aschaffenburg, Bad Homburg vor der Höhe, Rüsselsheim, Wetzlar and Marburg.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The city is divided into 46 city districts (*Stadtteile*), which are in turn divided into 121 city boroughs (*Stadtbezirke*) and 448 electoral districts (*Wahlbezirke*).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The 46 city districts combine into 16 area districts (*Ortsbezirke*), which each have a district committee and chairperson.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The largest city district by population and area is Sachsenhausen, while the smallest is Altstadt, Frankfurt's historical center.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Some larger housing areas are often falsely called city districts, even by locals, like Nordweststadt (part of Niederursel, Heddernheim and Praunheim), Goldstein (part of Schwanheim), Riedberg (part of Kalbach-Riedberg) and Europaviertel (part of Gallus).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Bankenviertel (*banking district*), Frankfurt's financial district, is also not an administrative city district (it covers parts of the western Innenstadt district, the southern Westend district and the eastern Bahnhofsviertel district).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Many city districts are incorporated suburbs (*Vororte*) or were previously independent cities, such as Höchst.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Some like Nordend and Westend arose during the rapid growth of the city in the Gründerzeit following the Unification of Germany, while others were formed from territory which previously belonged to other city district(s), such as Dornbusch and Riederwald.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Until the year 1877 the city's territory consisted of the present-day inner-city districts of Altstadt, Innenstadt, Bahnhofsviertel, Gutleutviertel, Gallus, Westend, Nordend, Ostend and Sachsenhausen.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] At the end of the 19th century the city of Frankfurt was enlarged.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The central train station was built in 1888 to support the incorporation of existing population centers.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Bornheim was incorporated in 1877, followed by Bockenheim in 1895.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Seckbach, Niederrad and Oberrad followed on 1 July 1900.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The *Landkreis Frankfurt* was finally dispersed on 1 April 1910, and therefore Berkersheim, Bonames, Eckenheim, Eschersheim, Ginnheim, Hausen, Heddernheim, Niederursel, Praunheim, Preungesheim and Rödelheim joined the city.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In the same year a new city district, Riederwald, was created on territory that had formerly belonged to Seckbach and Ostend.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] On 1 April 1928 the City of Höchst became part of Frankfurt, as well as its city districts Sindlingen, Unterliederbach and Zeilsheim.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Simultaneously the *Landkreis Höchst* was dispersed with its member cities either joining Frankfurt (Fechenheim, Griesheim, Nied, Schwanheim, Sossenheim) or joining the newly established *Landkreis* of Main-Taunus-Kreis.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Dornbusch became a city district in 1946.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] It was created on territory that had formerly belonged to Eckenheim and Ginnheim.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] On 1 August 1972, Hesse's smaller suburbs of Harheim, Kalbach, Nieder-Erlenbach, and Nieder-Eschbach became districts while other neighboring suburbs chose to join the Main-Taunus-Kreis, the Landkreis Offenbach, the Kreis Groß-Gerau, the Hochtaunuskreis, the Main-Kinzig-Kreis or the Wetteraukreis.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Bergen-Enkheim was the last suburb to become part of Frankfurt on 1 January 1977.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Flughafen became an official city district in 1979.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] It covers the area of Frankfurt Airport that had belonged to Sachsenhausen and the neighboring city of Mörfelden-Walldorf.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt's youngest city district is Frankfurter Berg.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Kalbach was officially renamed Kalbach-Riedberg in 2006 because of the large residential housing development in the area known as Riedberg.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Together with these towns (and some larger nearby towns, e.g., Hanau, Rodgau, Dreieich, Langen) Frankfurt forms a contiguous built-up urban area called *Stadtregion Frankfurt* which is not an official administrative district.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The urban area had an estimated population of 2.3 million in 2010, and is the 13th-largest urban area in the EU.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt has a temperate oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*, Trewartha: *Dobk*).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Its climate features cool winters with frequent rain showers and overcast skies, and warm summers.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The average annual temperature is 11.4 °C (52.5 °F), with monthly mean temperatures ranging from 2.7 °C (36.9 °F) in January to 20.8 °C (69.4 °F) in July.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The city is one of the warmest in Germany in winter.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The growing season is longer when compared to the rest of Germany, thus resulting in an early arrival of springtime in the region, with trees typically leafing out already toward the end of March.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Winters in Frankfurt are generally mild or at least not freezing with a small possibility of snow, especially in January and February but dark and often overcast.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is, on average, covered with snow only for around 10 to 20 days per year.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The temperature falls below 0 °C on about 64 days and the daily maximum stays below freezing for about 10 days on average per year.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Because of the mild climate in the region, there are some well-known wine regions in the vicinity such as Rhenish Hesse, Rheingau, Franconia (wine region) and Bergstraße (route).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] There is also a microclimate on the northern bank of the river Main which allows palms, fig trees, lemon trees and southern European plants to grow in that area.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The area is called the "Nizza" (the German word for the southern French town Nice) and is one of the biggest parks with Mediterranean vegetation north of the Alps.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] With a population of 763,380 (2019) within its administrative boundaries and of 2,300,000 in the actual urban area, Frankfurt is the fifth-largest city in Germany, after Berlin, Hamburg, Munich and Cologne.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Central Frankfurt has been a *Großstadt* (a city with at least 100,000 residents by definition) since 1875.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] With 414,576 residents in 1910, it was the ninth largest city in Germany and the number of inhabitants grew to 553,464 before World War II.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] After the war, at the end of the year 1945, the number had dropped to 358,000.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In the following years, the population grew again and reached an all-time-high of 691,257 in 1963.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] It dropped again to 592,411 in 1986 but has increased since then.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] According to the demographic forecasts for central Frankfurt, the city will have a population up to 813,000 within its administrative boundaries in 2035 and more than 2.5 million inhabitants in its urban area.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] As of 2015, Frankfurt had 1909 ultra high-net-worth individuals, the sixth-highest number of any city in the world.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] During the 1970s, the state government of Hesse wanted to expand the city's administrative boundaries to include the entire urban area.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] This would have made Frankfurt officially the second-largest city in Germany after Berlin with up to 3 million inhabitants.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] However, because local authorities did not agree, the administrative territory is still much smaller than its actual urban area.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] According to data from the city register of residents, 51.2% of the population had a *migration background* as of 2015, which means that a person or at least one of their parents was born with foreign citizenship.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] For the first time, a majority of the city residents had an at least part non-German background.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Moreover, three of four children in the city under the age of six had full or partial immigrant backgrounds, and 27.7% of residents had a foreign citizenship.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Because of this the city is often considered to be a multicultural city, and has been compared to New York City and London.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt has the largest Moroccan community in Germany, numbering about 8,000 people, and the Rhine-Main area has about 20,000.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Many Moroccans came as guest workers in the 1970s.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt is historically a Protestant-dominated city.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] However, during the 19th century, an increasing number of Catholics moved to Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] As of 2013, the largest Christian denominations were Catholicism (22.7% of the population) and Protestantism, especially Lutheranism (19.4%).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Jewish community has a history dating back to medieval times and has always ranked among the largest in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] More than 7,200 inhabitants are affiliated with the Jewish community, making it the third largest in Germany after Berlin and Munich.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Frankfurt has a Muslim community estimated at 12% in 2006.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] According to calculations based on census data for 21 countries of origin, the number of Muslim migrants in Frankfurt amounted to about 84,000 in 2011, making up 12.6% of the population.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The most prevalent countries of origin were Turkey and Morocco.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Ahmadiyya Noor Mosque, constructed in 1959, is the city's largest mosque and the third largest in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In 2020, the number of Muslims in Frankfurt's total population was estimated at 18%.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The current mayor is Mike Josef of the Social Democratic Party, who took the office on 11 May 2023.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The Frankfurt am Main city council (*Stadtverordnetenversammlung*) governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] It is located in the city's medieval town hall, Römer, which is also used for representative and official purposes.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] For elections to the Hesse State Parliament, Frankfurt am Main is split up into six constituencies.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In total 15 delegates represent the city in the Landtag in Wiesbaden.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] The last election took place in October 2018.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Delegates from Frankfurt often serve high-ranking positions in Hessian politics, e.g.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Michael Boddenberg is Hessian Minister of Finance and Boris Rhein was elected President of the Landtag of Hesse in 2019.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] For federal elections which are held every four years, Frankfurt is split up into two constituencies.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] In the German federal election 2017, Matthias Zimmer (CDU) and Bettina Wiesmann were elected to the Bundestag by directe mandate in Frankfurt am Main I and Frankfurt am Main II respectively.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Nicola Beer (FDP), Achim Kessler (Linke), Ulli Nissen (SPD) and Omid Nouripour (Greens) were elected as well.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p01] Nicola Beer resigned as a member of parliament in 2019 following her election to the European Parliament where she now serves as vice president.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt is one of the world's most important financial hubs and Germany's financial capital, followed by Hamburg and Stuttgart.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The city's importance as a financial hub has risen since the eurozone crisis.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] According to an annual study by Cushman & Wakefield, the European Cities Monitor (2010), Frankfurt has been one of the top three cities for international companies in Europe, after London and Paris, since the survey started in 1990.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is the only German city considered to be an alpha world city (category 3) as listed by the Loughborough University group's 2010 inventory, which was a promotion from the group's 2008 inventory when it was ranked as an alpha minus world city (category 4).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] With more than 922 jobs per 1,000 inhabitants, Frankfurt has the highest concentration of jobs in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] On work days and Saturdays, one million people commute from all over the Rhein-Main-Area.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The city is expected to benefit from international banks relocating jobs from London to Frankfurt as a result of Brexit to retain access to the EU market.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Thus far, Morgan Stanley, Citigroup Inc., Standard Chartered Plc and Nomura Holdings Inc. announced they would move their EU headquarters to Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt is home to two important central banks: the German Bundesbank and the European Central Bank (ECB).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The European Central Bank (*Europäische Zentralbank*) is one of the world's most important central banks with a balance sheet total of around 7 trillion.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The ECB sets monetary policy for the Eurozone, consisting of 19 EU member states that have adopted the Euro (€) as their common currency.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] From 1998 the ECB Headquarters have been located in Frankfurt, first in the Eurotower at Willy-Brandt-Platz and in two other nearby high-rises.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The new Seat of the European Central Bank in the Ostend district, consisting of the former wholesale market hall (*Großmarkthalle*) and a newly built 185-meter skyscraper, was completed in late 2014.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The new building complex was designed to accommodate up to 2,300 ECB personnel.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The location is a few kilometers away from downtown and borders an industrial area as well as the Osthafen (*East Harbor*), It was primarily chosen because of its large premises which allows the ECB to install security arrangements without high fences.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The city honors the importance of the ECB by officially using the slogan "The City of the Euro" since 1998.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Deutsche Bundesbank (German Federal Bank), located in Ginnheim, was established in 1957 as the central bank for the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Until the euro (€) was introduced in 1999, the Deutsche Bundesbank was responsible for the monetary policy of Germany and for the German currency, the Deutsche Mark (DM).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Bundesbank was greatly respected for its control of inflation through the second half of the 20th century.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Today the Bundesbank is an integral part of the European System of Central Banks (ESCB) which is formed by all 27 EU member states.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Its balance sheet total is around 2,7 trillion, making it the 4th biggest central bank.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] In 2010, there were 63 national and 152 international banks that had a registered office in Frankfurt, including the headquarters of the major German banks, as well as 41 offices of international banks.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt is therefore known as Bankenstadt ("City of the banks") and nicknamed "Mainhattan" (a portmanteau of the local Main river and Manhattan in New York City) or "Bankfurt".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] 73,200 people were employed at banks in 2010.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Other major German banks include Frankfurter Volksbank, the second-largest *Volksbank* in Germany, Frankfurter Sparkasse and old-established private banks such as Bankhaus Metzler, Hauck & Aufhäuser and Delbrück Bethmann Maffei.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Many international banks have a registered or a representative office, e.g., Credit Suisse, UBS, Bank of America, Morgan Stanley, Goldman Sachs, Merrill Lynch, JPMorgan Chase & Co., Bank of China, Banco do Brasil, Itaú Unibanco Société Générale, BNP Paribas, SEB, Royal Bank of Scotland and Barclays.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Frankfurt Stock Exchange (*Frankfurter Wertpapierbörse*) began in the ninth century.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] By the 16th century Frankfurt had developed into an important European hub for trade fairs and financial services.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Today the Frankfurt Stock Exchange is by far the largest in Germany, with a turnover of more than 90 percent of the German stock market and is the third-largest in Europe after the London and the Paris.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The most important stock market index is the DAX, the index of the 30 largest German business companies listed at the stock exchange.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The stock exchange is owned and operated by Deutsche Börse, which is itself listed in the DAX.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Deutsche Börse also owns the European futures exchange Eurex and clearing company Clearstream.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] On 1 February 2012 European Commission blocked the proposed merger of Deutsche Börse and NYSE Euronext.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] "The merger between Deutsche Börse and NYSE Euronext would have led to a near-monopoly in European financial derivatives worldwide.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] These markets are at the heart of the financial system and it is crucial for the whole European economy that they remain competitive.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] We tried to find a solution, but the remedies offered fell far short of resolving the concerns." European competition commissioner Joaquín Almunia said.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is located downtown at the Börsenplatz.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Deutsche Börse's headquarters are formally registered in Frankfurt, but it moved most of its employees to a high-rise called "The Cube" in Eschborn in 2010, primarily due to significantly lower local corporate taxes.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt Trade Fair (*Messe Frankfurt*) has the third-largest exhibition site in the world with a total of 578,000 m2 (6,220,000 sq ft).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The trade fair premises are located in the western part between Bockenheim, the Westend and the Gallus district.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt and the river Rhine tributary Main acquired transnational economic importance in the Middle Ages.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] In 1337 the Holy Roman Emperor Louis IV of Bavaria issued a diploma privilege so that any other city was not allowed to establish a market or trade fair if this could harm the Frankfurt Trade Fair in any way.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] This imperial backing allowed Frankfurt to retain the commanding importance of the Frankfurt Trade Fair for centuries.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] In the Middle Ages the full range of manufactured and semi-processed commodities were trade at Frankfurt Fairs.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Messe Frankfurt GmbH, the owner and operator company, organized 87 exhibitions in 2010, of which 51 were in foreign countries.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is one of the largest trade fair companies with commercial activities in more than 150 countries.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt Airport is one of the busiest airports in the world and is also the single largest place of work in Germany with more than 500 companies, which employ 71,500 people (2010).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Fraport is the owner and operator of Frankfurt Airport.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is the airport's second-largest employer (19,800 workers in 2010).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Fraport also operates other airports worldwide, e.g., King Abdulaziz International Airport in Jeddah, Jorge Chávez International Airport in Lima and Antalya Airport.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The largest company at Frankfurt Airport is Lufthansa, Germany's flag carrier and Europe's largest airline.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Lufthansa employs 35,000 people in Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Lufthansa Aviation Center (LAC) is the main operation base of Lufthansa at Frankfurt Airport.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The airport serves as Lufthansa's primary hub with 157 worldwide destinations (compared to 110 destinations at Munich Airport, Lufthansa's second-largest hub).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Lufthansa Cargo is based in Frankfurt and operates its largest cargo center (LCC) at Frankfurt Airport.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Lufthansa Flight Training is also based here.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Condor is a German airline based at Frankfurt Airport.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Three of the four largest international accountancy and professional services firms *(Big Four)* are present.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) German headquarters are located at Tower 185.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] KPMG moved its European Headquarters (KPMG Europe LLP) to The Squaire.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu are present, while Ernst & Young is located in Eschborn.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The three major international credit rating agencies – Standard & Poor's, Moody's and Fitch Ratings – have their German headquarters in Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] DWS Investments is one of the largest investment trust company in Germany and manages €859 billion fund assets.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is one of the ten largest investment trust companies in the world.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Other large investment trust companies are Universal Investment, Allianz Global Investors Europe (a division of Allianz SE, and a top-five global active investment manager), Union Investment and Deka Investmentfonds.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Many of the largest international management consultancies are represented, including Arthur D.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Little, McKinsey & Company, Boston Consulting Group, Booz & Company, Oliver Wyman, Bearing Point, Capgemini, Bain & Company and Roland Berger Strategy Consultants.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Located in Frankfurt are the German headquarters of Jones Lang LaSalle and BNP Paribas Real Estate.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt has the highest concentration of lawyers in Germany, with one lawyer per 97 inhabitants (followed by Düsseldorf with a ratio of 1/117 and Munich with 1/124) in 2005.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] According to a ranking of German FOCUS magazine (November 2007) seven of the 48 largest advertising agencies in Germany are based in Frankfurt, including Havas, Dentsu, McCann-Erickson, Saatchi & Saatchi, JWT, and Publicis.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Around 570 companies of the advertising industry and 270 public relations companies are located in Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt is home to the German headquarters of Nestlé, the world's largest food company, located in Niederrad.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Other important food companies are Ferrero SpA (German headquarters) and Radeberger Gruppe KG, the largest private brewery group in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The South-Korean automobile manufacturer Kia Motors moved its European headquarters to Frankfurt in 2007.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] In the same year, Italian manufacturer Fiat opened its new German headquarters.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The automotive supplier Continental AG has the headquarters and a major manufacturing plant of its Chassis & Safety division (formerly ITT Automotive) located in Frankfurt Rödelheim.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Some of the largest German construction companies have offices, e.g., Bilfinger Berger, Hochtief, Züblin and BAM Deutschland.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt has Germany's highest concentration of homeowners.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] This is partly attributed to the financial sector, but also to its cosmopolitan nature, with expatriates and immigrants representing one-fourth of its population.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] For this reason, Frankfurt's property market often operates differently than the rest of the country where the prices are generally flatter.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt is one of Germany's leading tourist destinations.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] In addition to its infrastructure and economy, its diversity supports a vibrant cultural scene.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] This blend of attractions led 4.3 million tourists (2012) to visit Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Hotels in central Frankfurt offer 34,000 beds in 228 hotels, of which 13 are luxury hotels and 46 are first-class hotels.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt is home to companies from the chemical, transportation, telecommunication and energy industries.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] In addition, several cloud and fintech startups have their headquarters in Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Within Frankfurt's urban area are several important companies.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The business hub of Eschborn is located right at Frankfurt's city limits in the west and attracts businesses with significantly lower corporate taxes compared to Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Major companies in Eschborn include Ernst & Young, Vodafone Germany, Randstad NV and VR Leasing.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Deutsche Börse moved most of its employees to Eschborn in 2010.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Rüsselsheim is internationally known for its automobile manufacturer Opel, one of the biggest automobile manufacturers in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] With 20,000 employees in 2003, Opel was one of the five largest employers in Hesse.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Two DAX companies are located in Bad Homburg vor der Höhe, Fresenius SE & Co.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Other major companies are Hewlett-Packard, Bridgestone, Deutsche Leasing and Basler Versicherungen.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Kronberg im Taunus is home of the German headquarters of automobile manufacturer Jaguar Cars as well as the German headquarters of Accenture.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Lufthansa Systems, a subsidiary of Lufthansa, is located in Kelsterbach.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] LSG Sky Chefs, another subsidiary of Lufthansa, is located in Neu-Isenburg.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The German headquarters of Thomas Cook Group are based in Oberursel.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Langen is home to Deutsche Flugsicherung, the German air traffic control.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Römer, the German word for Roman, is a complex of nine houses that form the Frankfurt city hall (*Rathaus*).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The houses were acquired by the city council in 1405 from a wealthy merchant family.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The middle house became the city hall and was later connected with its neighbors.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The *Kaisersaal* ("Emperor's Hall") is located on the upper floor and is where the newly crowned emperors held their banquets.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Römer was partially destroyed in World War II and later rebuilt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The surrounding square, the Römerberg, is named after the city hall.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The former Altstadt (old town) quarter between the Römer and the Frankfurt Cathedral was redeveloped as the Dom-Römer Quarter from 2012 to 2018, including 15 reconstructions of historical buildings that were destroyed during World War II.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt Cathedral (*Frankfurter Dom*) is not a cathedral, but the main Catholic church, dedicated to St.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Gothic building was constructed in the 14th and 15th centuries on the foundation of an earlier church from the Merovingian time.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] From 1356 onwards, kings of the Holy Roman Empire were elected in this church, and from 1562 to 1792, Roman-German emperors were crowned there.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Bartholomew's has been called *Dom*, although it was never a bishop's seat.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] In 1867 it was destroyed by fire and rebuilt in its present style.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It was again partially destroyed in World War II and rebuilt in the 1950s.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The cathedral tower has a viewing platform open to the public at a height of 66 m (217 ft), accessed through a narrow spiral staircase with 386 steps.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt Central Station (*Frankfurt Hauptbahnhof*), which opened in 1888, was built as the central train station for Frankfurt to replace three smaller downtown train stations and to boost the needed capacity for travellers.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It was constructed as a terminus station and was the largest train station in Europe by floor area until 1915 when Leipzig Central Station was opened.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Its three main halls were constructed in a neo-Renaissance style, while the later enlargement with two outer halls in 1924 was constructed in neoclassical style.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Alte Oper is a former opera house, hence the name "Old Opera".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The opera house was built in 1880 by architect Richard Lucae.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It was one of the major opera houses in Germany until it was heavily damaged in World War II.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Until the late 1970s, it was a ruin, nicknamed "Germany's most beautiful ruin".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Former Frankfurt Lord Mayor Rudi Arndt called for blowing it up in the 1960s, which earned him the nickname "Dynamite-Rudi".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Public pressure led to its refurbishment and reopening in 1981.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Today, it functions as a famous concert hall, while operas are performed at the "new" Frankfurt Opera.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The inscription on the frieze of the Alte Oper says: "*Dem Wahren, Schönen, Guten*" ("To the true, the beautiful, the good").
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Paul's Church is a national historic monument in Germany because it was the seat of the first democratically elected parliament in 1848.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It was established in 1789 as a Protestant church, but was not completed until 1833.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Its importance has its roots in the Frankfurt Parliament, which met in the church during the revolutionary years of 1848/49 in order to write a constitution for a united Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The attempt failed because the monarchs of Prussia and Austria did not want to lose power.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] In 1849, Prussian troops ended the democratic experiment by force and the parliament dissolved; the building was once more used for religious services.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Paul's was partially destroyed in World War II with its interior significantly damaged.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It was quickly and symbolically rebuilt after the war albeit with modern alterations particularly to the interior; today it is used mainly for exhibitions and events.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Archaeological Garden contains small parts of the oldest recovered buildings: an ancient Roman settlement and the Frankfurt Royal Palace (*Kaiserpfalz Frankfurt*) from the sixth century.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The garden is located between the Römerberg and the cathedral.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It was discovered after World War II when the area was heavily bombed and later partly rebuilt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The remains were preserved and are now open to the public.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] From 2013 until 2015 an event building, the Stadthaus ("City house"), has been built on top of the garden, but it remains open to the public free of charge.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Wertheim House is the only timbered house in the Altstadt district that survived the heavy bombings of World War II undamaged.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is located on the Römerberg next to the Historical Museum.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Saalhof is the oldest conserved building in the Altstadt district and dates to the 12th century.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It was used as an exhibition hall by Dutch clothiers when trade fairs were held during the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Saalhof was partly destroyed in World War II and later rebuilt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Today it serves as a part of the Historical Museum.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Eiserner Steg (Iron Bridge) is a pedestrian-only bridge across the Main that connects Römerberg and Sachsenhausen.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It was built in 1868 and was the second bridge to cross the river.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] After World War II, when it was blown up by the Wehrmacht, it was quickly rebuilt in 1946.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Today some 10,000 people cross the bridge on a daily basis.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt is one of two sites of the German National Library (*Deutsche Nationalbibliothek*), the other being Leipzig.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Deutsche Nationalbibliothek is a universal library in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Eschenheim Tower (*Eschenheimer Turm*) was erected at the beginning of the 15th century and served as a city gate as part of late-medieval fortifications.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is the oldest and most unaltered building in the Innenstadt district.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Catherine's Church is the largest Protestant church, dedicated to Catherine of Alexandria, a martyred early Christian saint.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is located downtown at the entrance to the Zeil, the central pedestrian shopping street.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Although today Hauptwache is mostly associated with the inner-city underground train station of the same name, the name originates from a baroque building on the square above the station.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Hauptwache building was constructed in 1730 and was used as a prison, therefore the name that translates as "main guard-house".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Today the square surrounding the building is also called "Hauptwache" (formal "An der Hauptwache").
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Frankfurter Hof is a landmark downtown hotel at Kaiserplatz, built from 1872 to 1876.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is part of Steigenberger Hotels group and is considered the city's most prestigious.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Leonhard, on the Main close to the bridge Eiserner Steg, is a Catholic late Gothic hall church, derived from a Romanesque style basilica beginning in 1425.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It is the only one of nine churches in the Old Town that survived World War II almost undamaged.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The parish serves the English-speaking community.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The church has been under restoration from 2011 until 2019.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Around the city centre there are widespread quarters full of Gründerzeit architecture.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Buildings of that type often sport richly decorated façades in the form of Historicism such as Gothic Revival, Renaissance Revival, German Renaissance and Baroque Revival.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Around the city center of Frankfurt are several former independent villages, now part of the city, with timber-framed centres and even whole old towns like Höchst, Seckbach, Niederursel and Bergen-Enkheim.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Overall there are around 14.500 buildings in Frankfurt built before 1919 and around 3.000 of them are timber framed houses.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt is unique among German cities with regards to skyscrapers.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Since the 1970s some of the tallest buildings in Germany have been built along the Mainzer Landstrasse.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Main Tower was completed in 1999 with its top floor skydeck and penthouse restaurant designed to be open to tourists.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Frankfurt hosts 20 out of Germany's 21 skyscrapers.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Most skyscrapers and high-rise office buildings are located in the financial district (Bankenviertel), around the trade fair premises (Europaviertel) and at Mainzer Landstraße between Opernplatz and Platz der Republik, which connects the two areas.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Henninger Turm was opened in the 1960s and the silo was topped by a revolving restaurant designed to be a landmark.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The Henninger Turm was extensively refurbished and is now a residential high-rise.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The first high-rise building boom came in the 1970s when Westend Gate (then called *Plaza Büro Center*) and Silberturm were constructed and became the tallest buildings in Germany with a height of 159.3 meters and 166.3 meters, respectively.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Around the same time, Frankfurter Büro Center and City-Haus (142.4 meters and 142.1 meters) were constructed at Mainzer Landstraße and Eurotower (148.0 meters) and Garden Tower (127.0 meters; then called *Helaba-Hochhaus*) were constructed in the financial district.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] None of the buildings constructed during the 1980s surpassed Silberturm.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] The most famous buildings from this decade are the Deutsche Bank Twin Towers at Taunusanlage, both 155.0 meters tall.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Messeturm, built on the trade fair site, reached a height of 256.5 meters (842 ft) and became the tallest building in Europe by 1991.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] It was overtaken by the 259 m-high (850 ft) Commerzbank Tower in 1997.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] Other tall buildings from this decade are Westendstrasse 1 (208 meters (682 ft)), Main Tower (200 meters (660 ft)) and Trianon (186 meters (610 ft)).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] In 21st-century Frankfurt, more high-rise buildings and skyscrapers (e.g., Skyper, Opernturm, Tower 185, Seat of the European Central Bank, Taunusturm) emerged, but none have surpassed Commerzbank Tower.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p02] With a large forest, many parks, the Main riverbanks and the two botanical gardens, Frankfurt is considered a "green city": More than 50 percent of the area within the city limits are protected green areas.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] With more than 30 museums, Frankfurt has one of the largest variety of museums in Europe.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Most museums are part of the Museumsufer, located on the front row of both sides of the Main riverbank or nearby, which was created on an initiative by cultural politician Hilmar Hoffmann.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Ten museums are located on the southern riverbank in Sachsenhausen between the Eiserner Steg and the Friedensbrücke.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The street itself, Schaumainkai, is partially closed to traffic on Saturdays for Frankfurt's largest flea market.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Explora Museum+Wissenschaft+Technik (Explora Museum of Science and Engineering) in the Nordend district was closed in 2016.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Most museums open around 10:00 am local time, and it is possible to comfortably visit four museums in one day, a fact many tourists take advantage of.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Eurodance and Trance music originated in Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In 1989 German producers Michael Münzing and Luca Anzilotti (under the pseudonyms Benito Benites and John "Virgo" Garrett III) formed the Snap! project.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Snap! songs combined Rap and Soul vocals adding rhythm by using computer technology and mixing electronic sounds, bass and drums.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] By doing so a new genre was born: Eurodance.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In the early 1990s, DJs including Sven Väth and DJ DAG (of Dance 2 Trance) first played a harder, deeper style of acid house that became popular worldwide over the next decade as Trance music.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Some of the early and most influential Eurodance, Trance and Techno acts, e.g., La Bouche, Jam and Spoon, Magic Affair, Culture Beat, Snap!, Dance 2 Trance, Oliver Lieb and Hardfloor, and record labels such as Harthouse and Eye Q, were based in the city in the early 1990s.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt offers a variety of restaurants, bars, pubs and clubs.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Clubs concentrate in and around downtownand in the Ostend district, mainly close to Hanauer Landstraße.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Restaurants, bars and pubs concentrate in Sachsenhausen, Nordend, Bornheim and Bockenheim.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In electronic music, Frankfurt was a pioneering city in the late 1980s and early 1990s, with renowned DJs including Sven Väth, Marc Trauner, Scot Project and Kai Tracid.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] One of the main venues of the early Trance music sound was the Omen nightclub from 1988 to 1998.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Another popular disco club of the 1980s–1990s and a hotspot for Techno/Trance music was the Dorian Gray, which was located within Terminal 1 at Frankfurt Airport from 1978 to 2000.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Notable live music venues of the past include the Sinkkasten Arts Club (1971–2011) and the King Kamehameha Club (1999–2013).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Among the most popular active rock and pop concert venues is the Batschkapp in Seckbach, which opened in 1976 as a center for autonomous and left-wing counterculture.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In a 2001 ranking by the University of Liverpool, Frankfurt was rated the richest city in Europe by GDP per capita, followed by Karlsruhe, Paris and Munich.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt was voted the seventh in the Mercer Quality of Living Survey by the Mercer Quality of Living Survey (2012), seventh in the Mercer Quality of Living Survey (2010) and 18th at the Economist's World's Most Liveable Cities Survey (2011).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] According to an annual citizen survey (2010), arranged by the city council, 66 percent inhabitants are satisfied or highly satisfied with the city, while only 6 percent said that they are dissatisfied.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Compared to the 1993's survey the number of satisfied inhabitants has grown about 22 percent while the number of dissatisfied inhabitants was reduced by 8 percent.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] 84 percent of the inhabitants like to live in Frankfurt, 13 percent would rather choose to live somewhere else.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] 37 percent are satisfied with the public safety (1993: only 9 percent), 22 percent are dissatisfied (1993: 64 percent).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt consistently has the highest levels of crime per 100,000 inhabitants in Germany (15.976 crimes per annum in 2008) and is therefore dubbed the German "crime capital".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The rate for personal safety-relevant crimes such as murder, manslaughter, rape or bodily harm, is 3.4 percent, placing Frankfurt twelfth in the ranking (related to the official 680,000-inhabitant figure) or number 21 (related to the one-million-figure).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In 2018, the state of Hesse, where Frankfurt is located, was ranked the third-safest state in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The city can be accessed from around the world via Frankfurt Airport (*Flughafen Frankfurt am Main*) located 12 km (7 mi) southwest of downtown.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The airport has four runways and serves 265 nonstop destinations.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Run by transport company Fraport it ranks among the world's busiest airports by passenger traffic and is the busiest airport by cargo traffic in Europe.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The airport also serves as a hub for Condor and as the main hub for German flag carrier Lufthansa.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] It is the busiest airport in Europe in terms of cargo traffic, and the fourth busiest in Europe in terms of passenger traffic behind London Heathrow Airport, Paris Charles de Gaulle Airport and Amsterdam Airport Schiphol.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Passenger traffic at Frankfurt Airport in 2018 was 69,510,269 passengers.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] A third terminal is being constructed (planned to open in 2026).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The third terminal will increase the capacity of the airport to more than 90 million passengers per year.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The airport can be reached by car or bus and has two railway stations, one for regional and one for long-distance traffic.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The S-Bahn lines S8 and S9 (direction *Offenbach Ost* or *Hanau Hbf*) departing at the regional station take 10–15 minutes from the airport to Frankfurt Central Station and onwards to Hauptwache station downtown.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The IC and ICE trains departing at the long-distance station take 10 minutes to Frankfurt Central Station.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Despite the name, Frankfurt Hahn Airport (*Flughafen Frankfurt-Hahn*) is situated approximately 120 km (75 mi) from the city in Lautzenhausen (Rhineland-Palatinate).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] An hourly bus service runs from Frankfurt Central Station, taking just over 2 hours.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Passenger traffic at Hahn Airport in 2010 was 3.5 million.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt Egelsbach Airport (*Flugplatz Frankfurt-Egelsbach*) is a busy general aviation airport located south-east of Frankfurt Airport, near Egelsbach.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt is a traffic hub for the German motorway (*Autobahn*) system.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Frankfurter Kreuz is an Autobahn interchange close to the airport, where the Bundesautobahn 3 (A3), Cologne to Würzburg, and the Bundesautobahn 5 (A5), Basel to Hanover, meet.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] With approximately 320,000 cars passing through it every day, it is Europe's most heavily used interchange.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Bundesautobahn 66 (A66) connects Frankfurt with Wiesbaden in the west and Fulda in the east.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Bundesautobahn 661 (A661) is mainly a commuter motorway that starts in the south (Egelsbach), runs through the eastern part and ends in the north (Oberursel).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Bundesautobahn 648 (A648) is a very short motorway in the western part which primarily serves as a fast connection between the A 66 and the Frankfurt Trade Fair.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The A5 in the west, the A3 in the south and the A661 in the northeast form a ring road around the inner city districts and define a Low-emission zone (*Umweltzone*; established in 2008), meaning that vehicles have to meet certain emission criteria to enter the zone.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The streets of central Frankfurt are usually congested with cars during rush hour.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Some areas, especially around the shopping streets Zeil, Goethestraße and Freßgass, are pedestrian-only streets.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt Hauptbahnhof *(*often abbreviated as *Frankfurt (Main) Hbf* or *F-Hbf*) is the largest railway station in Germany by railway traffic.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] By daily passenger volume, it ranks second (493,000 each) after Hamburg Central Station (550,000).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] It is located between the Gallus, the Gutleutviertel and the Bahnhofsviertel district, not far away from the trade fair and the financial district.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] It serves as a major hub for long-distance trains (InterCity, ICE) and regional trains as well as for Frankfurt's public transport system.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] It is a stop for most of ICE high-speed lines, making it Germany's most important ICE station.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] ICE Trains to London via the Channel Tunnel were planned for 2013.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] All Rhine-Main S-Bahn lines, two U-Bahn lines (U4, U5), several tram and bus lines stop there.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Regional and local trains are integrated in the Public transport system Rhein-Main-Verkehrsverbund (RMV), the second-largest integrated public transport system in the world, after Verkehrsverbund Berlin-Brandenburg.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt Airport can be accessed by two railway stations: Frankfurt Airport long-distance station (*Frankfurt Flughafen Fernbahnhof*) is only for long-distance traffic and connects the airport to the main rail network, with most of the ICE services using the Cologne-Frankfurt high-speed rail line.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The long-distance station is located outside the actual airport ground but has a connecting bridge for pedestrians to Terminal 1, concourse B.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt Airport regional station (*Frankfurt Flughafen Regionalbahnhof*) is for local S-Bahn trains (lines S8, S9) and regional trains.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The regional station is located within Terminal 1, concourse B.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt's third long-distance station is Frankfurt South station (*Frankfurt Südbahnhof*, often abbreviated as *Frankfurt (Main) Süd* or *F-Süd*), located in Sachsenhausen.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] It is an important destination for local trains and trams (lines 15, 16 and 18) and the terminal stop for four U-Bahn lines (U1, U2, U3, U8) as well as three S-Bahn lines (S3, S4, S5).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Frankfurt Trade Fair offers two railway stations: Messe station is for local S-Bahn trains (lines S3-S6) and is centrally located amid trade fair premises, while Festhalle/Messe station is served by U-Bahn line U4 and is located at the north-east corner of the premises.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Two other major downtown railway stations are Konstablerwache and Hauptwache, located on each end of the Zeil.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] They are the main stations to change from east-to-west-bound S-Bahn trains to north-to-south-bound U-Bahn trains.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Konstablerwache station is the second-busiest railway station regarding daily passenger volume (98,000) after the central station.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The third-busiest railway station is Hauptwache station (93,000).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] This Station, located in Bockenheim, is served by north-heading Long-Distance ICE trains, multiple regional trains, and four commuter S-Bahn lines (S3, S4, S5, S6).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Additionally, it is an important terminal stop for three "Metrobus" lines (M32, M36, M73).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] There are three stations for intercity bus services in Frankfurt: one at the south side of the Central Station, one at the Terminal 2 of the airport and another one at Stephanstraße.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The city has two rapid transit systems: the U-Bahn and the S-Bahn, as well as an above-ground tram system.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Information about the U- and S-Bahn can be found on the website of the RMV.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Nine S-Bahn lines (S1 to S9) connect Frankfurt with the densely populated Rhine Main Region.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Most routes have at least 15-minute service during the day, either by one line running every 15 minutes, or by two lines servicing one route at a 30-minute interval.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] All lines, except line S7, run through the Frankfurt City Tunnel and serve stations at Ostendstraße, Konstablerwache, Hauptwache, Taunusanlage and Frankfurt Central Station.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] When leaving the city the S-Bahn travels above ground.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] It provides access to the trade fair (S3, S4, S5, S6), the airport (S8, S9), the stadium (S7, S8, S9) and nearby cities such as Wiesbaden, Mainz, Darmstadt, Rüsselsheim, Hanau, Offenbach am Main, Oberursel, Bad Homburg, Kronberg, Friedberg and smaller towns that are on the way.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The U-Bahn has nine lines (U1 to U9) serving Frankfurt and the larger suburbs of Bad Homburg and Oberursel in the north.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The trains that run on the U-Bahn are in fact light rail (*Stadtbahn*) as many lines travel along a track in the middle of the street instead of underground.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The minimum service interval is 2.5 minutes, although the usual pattern is that each line runs at 7.5- to 10-minute intervals, which produce between 3- and 5-minute intervals on downtown tracks shared by more than one line.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt has ten tram lines (11, 12, 14 to 21), with trams arriving usually every 10 minutes.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Many sections are served by two lines, combining to run at 5-minute intervals during rush-hour.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Trams only run above ground and serve more stops than the U-Bahn or the S-Bahn.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] A number of bus lines complete the Frankfurt public transport system.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Night buses replace U-Bahn and tram services between 1:30 am and 3:30 am.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The central junction for the night bus service is at the downtown square of Konstablerwache, where all night bus lines start and end.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Taxicabs can usually be found outside the major S-Bahn and U-Bahn stations, at the central station, the south station, the airport, the trade fair and in the crowded inner-city shopping streets.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The common way to obtain a taxi is to either call a taxi operator or to go to a taxi rank.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] However, although not the norm, one can hail a passing taxi on the street.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Uber ceased operations in Frankfurt on 9 November 2015 after operating in the city for 18 months.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] However, UberX and local cabs are available through the Uber app.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Deutsche Bahn makes bicycles available for hire through their Call a Bike service.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The bicycles are stationed all over the city, including at selected railway stations.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] They can easily be spotted because of their eye-catching silver-red color.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] To rent a specific bike, riders either call a service number to get an unlock code or reserve the bike via the smartphone application.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] To return the bike, the rider locks it within a designated return area (and calls the service number, if not booked via the app).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Nextbike also makes bicycles available for hire in Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] These can be spotted with their blue color scheme.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Cycle rickshaws (velotaxis), a type of tricycle designed to carry passengers in addition to the driver, are also available.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] These are allowed to operate in pedestrian-only areas and are therefore practical for sightseeing.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt has a network of cycle routes.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Many long-distance bike routes into the city have cycle tracks that are separate from motor vehicle traffic.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] A number of downtown roads are "bicycle streets" where the cyclist has the right of way and where motorized vehicles are only allowed access if they do not disrupt the cycle users.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In addition, cyclists are allowed to ride many cramped one-way streets in both directions.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] As of 2015, 15 percent of citizens used bicycles.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Since 15 June 2019, the use of e-scooters was officially permitted by the German federal government.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In Frankfurt, companies like Lime, TIER, Bird, voi., Dott or Bolt are offering their electric micro mobility vehicles for lease.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] However, their use is being regarded with increasing weariness due to frequent abuse (parking, speeding, vandalism, accidents) and has sparked a public debate about the need of further regulation of the e-scooter market.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The European Insurance and Occupational Pensions Authority (EIOPA) is an institution of the EU and part of the European System of Financial Supervisors that was created in response to the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt is one of two locations of the German Federal Financial Supervisory Authority (*Bundesanstalt für Finanzdienstleistungsaufsicht*, short: *BaFin*).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The BaFin is an independent federal institution and acts as Germany's financial regulatory authority.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Anti-Money Laundering Authority (AMLA) of the European Union (EU) is based in Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt is home to the German office of the International Finance Corporation (IFC), which is part of the World Bank Group.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The IFC promotes sustainable private sector investment in developing countries.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] As a profoundly international city, Frankfurt hosts 93 diplomatic missions (consulates and consulates-general).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Consulate General of the United States in Eckenheim is the largest American consulate in the world.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt hosts two universities and several specialist schools.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The two business schools are Goethe University Frankfurt's Goethe Business School and Frankfurt School of Finance & Management.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The oldest and best-known university is the Johann Wolfgang Goethe University, with locations in Bockenheim, Westend, and Riedberg, and the university hospital in Niederrad.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Goethe Business School is part of the university's House of Finance at Campus Westend.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Business School's Full-Time MBA program has more than 70% international students.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Frankfurt University of Applied Sciences was created out of several older organisations in 1971, and offers more than 38 study areas, in the arts, sciences, engineering and law.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In 2001, it became a specialist institution for Economics and Management, or FOM.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt School is consistently ranked among the best business schools in the world, attributed to its high research output and quality of undergraduate and graduate training.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt has the State Institution of Higher Learning for Artistic Education known as the Städelschule, founded in 1817 by Johann Friedrich Städel.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] It was taken over by the city in 1942 and turned into a state art school.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Music institutions are the Frankfurt University of Music and Performing Arts, and the Hoch Conservatory (Dr.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Hoch's Konservatorium) which was founded in 1878.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The International Ensemble Modern Academy is a significant institution for the study of contemporary music.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Sankt Georgen Graduate School of Philosophy and Theology (German:*Philosophisch-Theologische Hochschule Sankt Georgen*), a private institution with membership in the German Jesuit Association, has been located in Sachsenhausen since 1950.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt schools rank among the best-equipped schools nationwide for the availability of PCs and other media facilities.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In order to assure maintenance and support of the school PCs, the city in cooperation with the University of Applied Sciences launched the project Fraline – IT-Schul-Service, an initiative employing students to provide basic school IT-support.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The city is home to three Max Planck Society institutes: the Max Planck Institute for Legal History and Legal Theory, Max Planck Institute for Biophysics, and the Max Planck Institute for Brain Research.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The Frankfurt Institute for Advanced Studies, sponsored by several institutional and private sources, is involved in theoretical research in physics, chemistry, neuroscience, and computer science.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt is host to the *Römisch-Germanische-Kommission* (RGK), the German Archaeological Institute branch for prehistoric archeology in Germany and Europe.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The RGK is involved in a variety of research projects.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Its library, with more than 200,000 items, is one of the largest archeological libraries in the world.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Goethe University and Frankfurt University of Applied Sciences are involved in the Hessian Center for Artificial Intelligence ("hessian.AI").
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Two important daily newspapers are published.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The conservative *Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung*, also known as *FAZ*, was founded in 1949 and is the German newspaper with the widest circulation outside of Germany, with its editors claiming to deliver the newspaper to 148 countries every day.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The FAZ has a circulation of more than 380,000 copies daily.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The other important newspaper, the *Frankfurter Rundschau*, was first published in 1945 and has a daily circulation of more than 181,000.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Several magazines also originate from Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The local *Journal Frankfurt* is the best-known magazine for events, parties, and "insider tips".
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] *Öko-Test* is a consumer-oriented magazine that focuses on ecological topics.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] *Titanic* is a well-known and often criticized satirical magazine with a circulation of approximately 100,000.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt's first radio station was the Südwestdeutsche Rundfunkdienst AG (Southwest German Broadcast Service), founded in 1924.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Its successor service is the public broadcaster Hessischer Rundfunk (Hessian Broadcast Service).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] It is located at the "Funkhaus am Dornbusch" in the Dornbusch district and is one of the most important radio and television broadcasters in Hesse, with additional studios in Kassel, Darmstadt and Fulda.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Bloomberg TV and RTL Television have regional studios.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Other radio broadcasters include Main FM and Radio X.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] From August 1945 to October 2004, the American Forces Network (AFN) had broadcast from Frankfurt (AFN Frankfurt).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Due to troop reductions the AFN's location has been closed with AFN now broadcasting from Mannheim.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt is home to the German office of Reuters, a global news agency.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Associated Press and US-based international news agency Feature Story News have bureaux in Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt is home to several professional sports teams.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Some of them have won German Championships.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Basketball side Skyliners Frankfurt won the German Basketball Championship in 2004 and the German Cup in 2000.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Football sides Eintracht Frankfurt (formerly 1.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Frankfurt is host to the classic cycle race Eschborn-Frankfurt City Loop (known as *Rund um den Henninger-Turm* from 1961 to 2008).
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] The city hosts also the annual Frankfurt Marathon and the Ironman Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] In addition to the former, it is one of 13 global host locations to the J.P.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Morgan Corporate Challenge, Germany's biggest corporate sports event.
[src:andreas-storm/frankfurt-p03] Rhein-Main Eissport Club forms the base of the German bandy community.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2014.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The first female president of the university, Birgitta Wolff, was sworn into office in 2015, and was succeeded by Enrico Schleiff in 2021.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] 20 Nobel Prize winners have been affiliated with the university, including Max von Laue and Max Born.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university is also affiliated with 18 winners of the Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Goethe University is part of the IT cluster Rhine-Main-Neckar.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz, the Goethe University Frankfurt and the Technische Universität Darmstadt together form the Rhine-Main-Universities (RMU).
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The historical roots of the university can be traced back as far as 1484, when a City Council Library was established with a bequest from the patrician Ludwig von Marburg.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Merged with other collections, it was renamed City Library in 1668 and became the university library in 1914.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Depending on the country, the date of foundation is recorded differently.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] According to Anglo-American calculations, the founding date of Goethe University would be 1484.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] In Germany, the date on which the right to award doctorates is granted is considered the founding year of a university.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The modern history of the University of Frankfurt can be dated to 28 September 1912, when the foundation contract for the "Königliche Universität zu Frankfurt am Main" (**Royal University at Frankfurt on the Main**) was signed at the Römer, Frankfurt's town hall.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Royal permission for the university was granted on 10 June 1914, and the first enrollment of students began on 16 October 1914.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Members of Frankfurt's Jewish community, including the Speyer family, Wilhelm Ralph Merton, and the industrialists Leo Gans and Arthur von Weinberg donated two thirds of the foundation capital of the University of Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university has been best known historically for its Institute for Social Research (founded 1923), the institutional home of the Frankfurt School, a preeminent 20th-century school of philosophy and social thought.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Some of the well-known scholars associated with this school include Theodor Adorno, Max Horkheimer, and Jürgen Habermas, as well as Herbert Marcuse, Erich Fromm, and Walter Benjamin.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Other well-known scholars at the University of Frankfurt include the sociologist Karl Mannheim, the philosopher Hans-Georg Gadamer, the philosophers of religion Franz Rosenzweig, Martin Buber, and Paul Tillich, the psychologist Max Wertheimer, and the sociologist Norbert Elias.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The University of Frankfurt has at times been considered liberal, or left-leaning, and has had a reputation for Jewish and Marxist (or even Jewish-Marxist) scholarship.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] During the Nazi period, "almost one third of its academics and many of its students were dismissed for racial and/or political reasons—more than at any other German university".
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university also played a major part in the German student movement of 1968.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university also has been influential in the natural sciences and medicine, with Nobel Prize winners including Max von Laue and Max Born, and breakthroughs such as the Stern–Gerlach experiment.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] In recent years, the university has focused in particular on law, history, and economics, creating new institutes, such as the Institute for Law and Finance (ILF) and the Center for Financial Studies (CFS).
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] One of the university's ambitions is to become Germany's leading university for finance and economics, given the school's proximity to one of Europe's financial centers.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] In cooperation with Duke University's Fuqua School of Business, the Goethe Business School offers an MBA program.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Goethe University has established an international award for research in financial economics, the Deutsche Bank Prize in Financial Economics.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] In February 2026, the Johann Christian Senckenberg University Library at Goethe University returned five Nazi-looted books to the Jewish Community of Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] This marked the first time the university restituted looted property directly to the local community.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The books were identified through a provenance research project launched in 2020 and funded by the German Lost Art Foundation.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Among the returned volumes were books belonging to Julius Blau, a prominent lawyer and former chairman of the Israelite Community, and his son Ernst Blau, a librarian who died in the Gurs concentration camp.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university consists of 16 faculties.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university is involved in the Hessian Center for Artificial Intelligence (hessian.AI).
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The Westend Campus is the main location with the Presidential Board based in the Presidential and Administration Building (PA).
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Farben Building and numerous new buildings, including the House of Finance and the central lecture theatre building.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] In addition to the central administration, most departments, with the exception of Medicine and Natural Sciences, are or have been located here since 2001.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The Language and Art Building (SKW) (FB 09) is currently the new building on campus.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] This campus is of particular historical significance, as Goethe University has inherited history through the acquisition of real estate.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] "Campus Westend" of the university is dominated by the IG Farben Building by architect Hans Poelzig, an example of the modernist New Objectivity style.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The style for the IG Farben Building was originally chosen as "a symbol for the scientific and mercantile German manpower, made out of iron and stone", as the IG Farben director at the time of construction, Baron von Schnitzler, stated in his opening speech in October 1930.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] After the university took over the complex in the 1990s, new buildings were added to the campus.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] On 30 May 2008, the House of Finance relocated to a new building designed by the architects Kleihues+Kleihues, following the style of the IG Farben Building.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The upper floors of the House of Finance building have several separate offices as well as shared office space for researchers and students.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The ground floor is open to the public and welcomes visitors with a spacious, naturally lit foyer that leads to lecture halls, seminar rooms, and the information center, a 24-hour reference library.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The ground floor also accommodates computer rooms and a café.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The floors, walls and ceiling of the foyer are decorated with a grid design that is continued throughout the entire building.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The flooring is inspired by Raphael's mural, *The School of Athens*.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The emergence of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Basic Law (Grundgesetz) can be traced back to the Frankfurter Dokumente that were handed over in the I.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The Riedberg campus, with university buildings built from around 1970, is home to the Departments of Physics, Biochemistry, Chemistry and Pharmacy, Biosciences and (largely) Earth Sciences, the Science Garden and a lecture theatre centre with the natural sciences departmental library.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The Niederrad campus is home to the University Hospital and the Department of Medicine, with buildings and facilities that have grown historically since the 19th century as well as modern complexes.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Campus Ginnheim is the location of the athletics grounds, multiple tennis and volleyball courts, the sports halls, and the University Sports Centre.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Ginnheim also houses many of the lecture halls for classes in physical education, sport psychology, and social sciences in sport.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university's relocation programme, which has been intensified since the mid-1990s, aims to create a de facto three-campus university in the future.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] To this end, the units currently located in the Bockenheim district are also to be relocated, but not the sports grounds.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The public Botanical Garden Frankfurt am Main at the end of Siesmayerstraße, formerly associated with the biology campus (1956–2011), has been transferred to the City of Frankfurt am Main and the responsibility of the Palmengarten.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Parts of the former Bockenheim campus, including the historic Jügelhaus, have been taken over by the Senckenberg Gesellschaft für Naturforschung, while other parts have been left to local urban development.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The formerly numerous other scattered university buildings in the Bockenheim district have been abandoned and partly demolished, partly put to other uses.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The Goethe Business School is a graduate business school at the university, established in 2004, part of the House of Finance at the Westend Campus and the IKB building.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] It is a non-profit foundation under private law held by the university.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Its board of directors is led by Rolf-Ernst Breuer, who was chairman of the board of Deutsche Bank until 2006.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The school has maintained a partnership in Executive Education with the Indian School of Business (ISB) since 2009.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The word/image mark used from 1980 to 2002 was developed by Adrian Frutiger.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] There are different types of basically the same logo.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] As old university logos never really "expire", they remain valid.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Since 2008, the university administration has made various changes to the practical name of the university and, accordingly, to the logo.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] On 26 September 2016, another logo was also registered at the German Patent and Trade Mark Office as an individual trade mark, consisting only of the words "GOETHE UNIVERSITY".
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] However, this logo is not currently in use.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The Deutsche Bank Prize in Financial Economics honors renowned researchers who have made influential contributions to the fields of finance and money and macroeconomics, and whose work has led to practical and policy-relevant results.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] It is awarded biannually, since 2005, by the Center for Financial Studies, in partnership with Goethe University Frankfurt.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The award carries an endowment of €50,000, which is donated by the Stiftungsfonds Deutsche Bank im Stifterverband für die Deutsche Wissenschaft.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Further information and archives on university policy work at Goethe University do not exist, which is why there is hardly any transparency about university policy.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] There are official publications on the Goethe University website, which must be made in accordance with the Hessian Higher Education Act.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] These can also be found in the German National Library.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Little can be said about the political significance of university politics due to the lack of transparency in university politics as a whole and the lack of interest in its activities.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Students are not very interested in university politics due to a voter turnout of less than 15% in recent years and the incidents and judgements against the AStA.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university management and the departments support numerous private and university-affiliated student groups, initiatives and private alumni organisations.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The student councils at Goethe University are legally regulated by the Hessian Higher Education Act.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] They are therefore not student initiatives in the traditional sense, as they are legally binding institutions without their own legal personality.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] New student initiatives are regularly created at Goethe University as part of the Deutschlandstipendium programme.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] These initiatives are supported by the non-material support programme for the Deutschlandstipendium from the Presidential Board of Goethe University.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Goethe University has its own non-exhaustive network of alumni organisations, a sponsors' association and its own e-mail distribution list for alumni.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Alumni organisations require formal recognition and approval by the university administration in order to be listed as official alumni associations.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Without such recognition, it is not possible for the association to list itself as an official alumni organisation of Goethe University.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Officers of these organisations are mostly current and former professors as well as people in leading positions at Goethe University.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The largest university-related alumni organisation with over 1,300 members is the Frankfurter Wirtschaftswissenschaftliche Gesellschaft (fwwg), which was founded in 1988 and is open to the Department of Economics.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Local, regional, national, European and international student initiatives have given rise to many parallel alumni networks that run in parallel and independently of each other.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] These include the alumni organisations of AIESEC, MTP – Marketing between Theory and Practice, European Law Students' Association, Erasmus Student Network and others.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Student initiatives such as green finance consulting, Goethe Club, Goethe Gruppe or Night of Science, as well as political university groups, are further hybrids between student initiatives and alumni organisations.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] Independent alumni organisations are not recognised as official alumni organisations at Goethe University.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] According to the QS World University Rankings for 2024, the university holds a global position of 302 and ranks 18th nationally.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] In the 2024 edition of the Times Higher Education World University Rankings, it is positioned between 201 and 250 internationally, and 22 to 24 within the country.
[src:andreas-storm/goethe-university-frankfurt] The university achieved its highest national ranking in the 2023 Academic Ranking of World Universities (ARWU), where it was placed between 151 and 200 globally, and 6 to 9 nationally.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Saarland was first established as a distinct political entity in 1920 after World War I as the Territory of the Saar Basin, which was occupied and governed by France under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Saarland was returned to Nazi Germany in the 1935 Saar status referendum.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Following World War II in Europe, the territory was occupied by France, then became the Saar Protectorate on 17 December 1947.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] After the 1955 Saar Statute referendum, it joined the Federal Republic of Germany as a state on 1 January 1957.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Saarland used its own currency, the Saar franc, and postage stamps issued specially for the territory until 1959.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The region of the Saarland was settled by the Celtic tribes of Treveri and Mediomatrici.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The most impressive relic of their time is the remains of a fortress of refuge at Otzenhausen in the north of the Saarland.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In the 1st century BC, the Roman Empire made the region part of its province of Belgica, and the Celtic population mixed with the Roman conquerors.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The region became wealthy, which can still be seen in the remains of Roman villas and villages.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Roman rule ended in the 5th century, when the Franks conquered the territory.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] For the next 1,300 years the region shared the history of the Kingdom of the Franks, the Carolingian Empire and the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The region of the Saarland was divided into several small territories, some of which were ruled by sovereigns of adjoining regions.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Most important of the local rulers were the counts of Nassau-Saarbrücken.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Within the Holy Roman Empire these territories gained a wide range of independence, threatened, however, by the French kings, who sought from the 17th century onwards to incorporate all the territories on the western side of the river Rhine.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] They invaded the area in 1635, 1676, 1679, and 1734, extending their realm to the river Saar and establishing the city and stronghold of Saarlouis in 1680.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] It was not the king of France but the armies of the French Revolution who terminated the independence of the states in the region of the Saarland.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] After 1792 they conquered the region and made it part of the French Republic.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] While a strip in the west belonged to the Moselle department, the centre in 1798 became part of the Sarre department, and the east became part of the Mont-Tonnerre department.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] After the defeat of Napoleon in 1815, the region was divided again.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Most of it became part of the Prussian Rhine Province.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Another part in the east, corresponding to the present Saarpfalz district, was allocated to the Kingdom of Bavaria.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] A small part in the northeast was ruled by the Duke of Oldenburg.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] On 31 July 1870, the French Emperor Napoleon III ordered an invasion across the River Saar to seize Saarbrücken.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The first shots of the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71 were fired on the heights of Spichern during the Battle of Spicheren, south of Saarbrücken.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The Saar region became part of the German Empire which came into existence on 18 January 1871, during the course of the war.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In 1921, the Saargebiet was occupied by Britain and France under the provisions of the Treaty of Versailles.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The occupied area included portions of the Prussian Rhine Province and the Bavarian Rhenish Palatinate.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In practice the region was administered by France.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In 1920, this was formalized by a 15-year mandate by the League of Nations.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In 1933, a considerable number of communists and other political opponents of Nazism fled to the Saar, as it was the only part of Germany that remained outside national administration following the First World War.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] As a result, anti-Nazi groups agitated for the Saarland to remain under French administration.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] However, with most of the population being ethnically German, such views were considered suspect or even treasonous, and therefore found little support.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] When the original 15-year term was over, a plebiscite was held in the territory on 13 January 1935 in which 90.8 percent of those voting favoured rejoining Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Following the referendum Josef Bürckel was appointed on 1 March 1935 as the German Reich's commissioner for reintegration (*Reichskommissar für die Rückgliederung des Saarlandes*).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Once the reincorporation was accomplished, on 17 June 1936 his title was changed to *Reichskommissar für das Saarland* (Reich Commissioner for the Saarland).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In September 1939, in response to the German invasion of Poland, French forces invaded the Saarland in a half-hearted offensive, occupying some villages and meeting little resistance, before withdrawing.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] After 8 April 1940 Bürckel's title was changed again to *Reichskommissar für die Saarpfalz* (Reich Commissioner for the Saar Palatinate); finally, after 11 March 1941, Bürckel was made *Reichsstatthalter in der Westmark* (Reich Governor of the Western Borderland).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] He died on 28 September 1944 and was succeeded by Willi Stöhr, who remained in office until the region fell to advancing American forces in March 1945.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] After World War II, the Saarland came under French occupation again and became the Saar Protectorate.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] France did not annex the Saar or expel the local German population, in contrast to the fate of the territories which were merged by Poland and the USSR.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In his speech "Restatement of Policy on Germany", made in Stuttgart on 6 September 1946, United States Secretary of State James F.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Byrnes stated the U.S. position on detaching the Saar from Germany: "The United States does not feel that it can deny to France, which has been invaded three times by Germany in 70 years, its claim to the Saar territory".
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The Saar and Ruhr areas were historically a central location for coal mining.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] This attracted the steel industry, which is essential for the production of munitions.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The Treaty of Paris (1951) established the European Coal and Steel Community, which led to the termination of the International Authority for the Ruhr (whose purpose was to regulate Ruhr coal and steel production and distribution).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] However, the Treaty sidestepped the issue of the Saar protectorate: an attached protocol stated Germany and France agreed the Treaty would have no bearing on their views of the status of the Saar.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In 1948, the French government established Saarland University under the auspices of the University of Nancy.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] It is the principal university in the state, the other being Saarland University of Applied Sciences (HTW Saar).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The Saarland was headed by a military governor from 30 August 1945: Gilbert Yves Edmond Grandval (1904–1981), who remained, on 1 January 1948, as High Commissioner, and from January 1952 – June 1955 as the first of two French ambassadors, his successor being Éric de Carbonnel (1910–1965) until 1956.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In 1954, France and the Federal Republic of Germany (West Germany) developed a detailed plan called the *Saarstatut* (Saar Statute) to establish an independent Saarland.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] It was signed as an agreement between the two countries on 23 October 1954 as one of the Paris Pacts, but a plebiscite held on 23 October 1955 rejected it by 67.7%.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] On 27 October 1956, the Saar Treaty declared that Saarland should be allowed to join West Germany, which it did on 1 January 1957.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] This was the last significant international border change in Europe until the fall of Communism over 30 years later.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The Saarland's unification with West Germany was sometimes referred to as the *Kleine Wiedervereinigung* ('little reunification', in contrast with the post-Cold War reunification with the GDR).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] After unification, the Saar franc remained as the territory's currency until West Germany's Deutsche Mark replaced it on 7 July 1959.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The Saar Treaty established that French, not English as in the rest of West Germany, should remain the first foreign language taught in Saarland schools; this provision was still largely followed after it was no longer binding.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Since 1971, Saarland has been a member of SaarLorLux, a euroregion created from Saarland, Lorraine, Luxembourg, Rhineland Palatinate, and Wallonia.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The state borders France (department of Moselle, which forms part of the region of Grand Est) to the south and west, Luxembourg (Grevenmacher District) to the west and Rhineland-Palatinate to the north and the east.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] It is named after the river Saar, a tributary of the Moselle (itself a tributary of the Rhine), which runs through the state from the south to the northwest.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Saarland is about the same size as neighboring Luxembourg with Luxembourg being 2,586sq km (998 sq mi) and Saarland at 2,570sq km (990sq mi).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Within Germany, it is slightly larger than the combined area of the three city-states (Berlin, Bremen, and Hamburg) but is by far the smallest of the *Flächenländer* ("area-states").
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] It is less than one sixth the size of Schleswig-Holstein, the next smallest German state.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] One third of the land area of the Saarland is covered by forest, one of the highest percentages in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The state is generally hilly; the highest mountain is the Dollberg with a height of 695.4 m (2,281 ft).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Most inhabitants live in a city agglomeration on the French border, surrounding the capital of Saarbrücken.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Saarland is the most religious state in Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The adherents of the Catholic Church comprise 56.8% of the population, organised in the two dioceses of Trier (comprising the formerly Prussian part of Saarland) and Speyer (for the smaller eastern formerly Palatine part).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] 17.5% of the Saarlandic population adhere to the Protestant Church in Germany (Evangelische Kirche in Deutschland, EKD), organised in the two Landeskirchen named Evangelical Church in the Rhineland and Evangelical Church of the Palatinate, both following the same former territorial partition.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] 25.7% are not affiliated with one of these churches.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Saarland has the highest concentration of Roman Catholics of any German state, and is the only state in which Catholics form an absolute majority (over 50%).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] After the 2022 state elections the previous Grand Coalition between the CDU and SPD, the two largest parties in the Landtag, was replaced by an SPD majority government, the only single-party majority government of any German state, led by minister-president Anke Rehlinger.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The gross domestic product (GDP) of the state was €35.4 billion in 2018, accounting for 1.1% of German economic output.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] GDP per capita adjusted for purchasing power was €32,800 or 109% of the EU27 average in the same year.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The GDP per employee was 93% of the EU average.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The GDP per capita was the second lowest of all states in West Germany.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Important income sources are the automobile industry, steel industry, ceramic industry and computer science and information systems industry.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In the past, coal mining was an important branch of industry.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] However, the last coal mine in Saarland closed in 2012, ending 250 years of coal mining history in the region.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The decision to close the mines was motivated by safety concerns about earthquakes in the region.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The unemployment rate stood at 5.8% in October 2018 and was higher than the national average but below the EU28 average.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Education in Saarland, follows the standard three-tiered structure of the German public system while maintaining strong ties to its cross-border location.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] After Grundschule (primary school), which typically lasts four years, students move into one of three main secondary tracks: Gymnasium, Gemeinschaftsschule, or Berufsschulen.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The Gymnasium track prepares students for academic studies and ends with the Abitur (higher education entrance qualification); in Saarland, it generally runs for eight years (G8).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Saarland is home to several key institutions that drive regional research and cross-border cooperation, including the administrative headquarters of the Franco-German University (DFH) in Saarbrücken.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Saarland University (Universität des Saarlandes), located primarily in Saarbrücken and Homburg, is particularly noted for its excellence in Computer Science and European Law, benefiting from its unique European location.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The University of Applied Sciences (Hochschule für Technik und Wirtschaft des Saarlandes - HTW) focuses on practical engineering, economics, and social sciences, maintaining strong links with the region's industrial base.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] A unique feature of higher education in the state is the Franco-German component, as Saarland University runs several integrated Franco-German programs and maintains close partnerships with institutions in neighboring France, fostering strong multilingual academic environments.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The region's main airport is Saarbrücken Airport which provides some domestic and European flights, it is located 13.7 km (9 mi) east of Saarbrücken.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Generally, residents of state would also use Luxembourg Airport and Frankfurt Airport in which both provides more domestic and international flights.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] People in the Saarland speak Rhine Franconian (in the southeast, very similar to that dialect spoken in the western part of the Palatinate) and Moselle Franconian (in the northwest, very similar to that dialect spoken along the river Moselle and the cities of Trier or even in Luxembourg).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Outside of the Saarland, specifically the Rhine-Franconian variant spoken in the state capital Saarbrücken is generally considered to be *the* Saarland dialect.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The two dialect regions are mainly separated by the *das* / *dat* isogloss; in the northwestern portion of the state, including cities such as Saarlouis, standard German *das* is pronounced with a final [t] instead of an [s].
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In general, both dialects are an integral part of Saarland identity.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Both dialects, particularly in their respective Saarland flavour, share many characteristic features, some of which will be explained below.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Women and girls are often referred to using the neuter pronoun *es*, with the pronunciation being something like *Ähs* ([ɛːs]): ***Ähs** hat mir's gesaat* ('**it** told me so', instead of '**she** told me so'; vs.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] High German: ***Sie** hat es mir gesagt*).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] This stems from the word *Mädchen* (girl) being neuter (*es* is correct when referring to words like *Mädchen* but would not be used by itself in reference to a woman).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The subjunctive in Rhine Franconian is normally composed with the words *dääd* ([dɛːt]) (High German *täte* = "would do") or *gänge* ("would go") as auxiliary verbs: *Isch dääd saan, dass...* ("I would say that...") instead of the High German *Ich würde sagen, dass...*.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Diphthongs are less common than in Standard German.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] This is because the Standard German diphthongs *ei* and *au* are each the result of a merger of two Middle High German vowels – however, these mergers did not take place in the Saarland, and only one of the two merged vowels is pronounced as a diphthong.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The front rounded vowels *ö*, *ü*, and *eu* are replaced by *e*, *i*, and *ei* respectively.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] French has had a considerable influence on the vocabulary, although the pronunciation of imported French words is usually quite different from their originals.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Popular examples include *Trottwaa* (from *trottoir*), *Fissääl* (from *ficelle*), and the imperative or greeting *aalleh!* (from *allez!*).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The English sentence "My house is green" is pronounced almost the same in the Rhine Franconian variant: *Mei Haus is grien* [maɪ̯ haʊ̯s ɪs gʁiːn].
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The main difference lies in the pronunciation of the ⟨r⟩ sound.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Regional beer brewer Karlsberg has taken advantage of the Saarlandish dialect to create clever advertising for its staple product, UrPils.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The French language has a special standing in Saarland due to its geographical proximity to France.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Today, a part of the population is able to speak French, and it is compulsory at many schools.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] Saarbrücken is also home to a bilingual *"Deutsch-Französisches Gymnasium"* (German-French high school).
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] In January 2014 the Saarland state government announced its aim of making the region fully bilingual in German and French by 2043.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] The Saar competed in the qualifying section of the 1954 FIFA World Cup, but failed after coming second to West Germany but ahead of Norway.
[src:andreas-storm/saarland] It also competed as Saar in the 1952 Summer Olympics and the field handball world championships in the beginning of the 1950s.
